1
00:00:36,945 --> 00:00:38,139
Panama.

2
00:00:39,647 --> 00:00:40,875
Panama?

3
00:00:41,082 --> 00:00:42,379
Best l could do, Andrew...

4
00:00:42,584 --> 00:00:45,849
...in the circumstances,
given your sins.

5
00:00:46,287 --> 00:00:48,050
They were baying for blood.

6
00:00:50,058 --> 00:00:51,753
l argued your case.

7
00:00:53,361 --> 00:00:56,262
''For his long service,
his fine brain in the balance...

8
00:00:56,464 --> 00:00:58,056
...against the gambling debts...

9
00:00:58,266 --> 00:01:01,861
...the blown cover and the wives.''

10
00:01:02,070 --> 00:01:04,231
The wives.

11
00:01:05,006 --> 00:01:07,566
So, a last chance.

12
00:01:07,775 --> 00:01:08,833
Panama.

13
00:01:09,611 --> 00:01:11,272
Keep the head down?

14
00:01:12,413 --> 00:01:13,471
Serve out my time?

15
00:01:13,681 --> 00:01:16,013
Not quite, Andrew.
We do have interests:

16
00:01:16,217 --> 00:01:19,846
The canal, vital artery.
There is work to be done.

17
00:01:22,523 --> 00:01:25,424
But for God's sake,
be careful out there, man.

18
00:01:25,627 --> 00:01:28,152
There's a nasty web
of money-laundering...

19
00:01:28,363 --> 00:01:30,388
...drug trafficking and corruption.

20
00:01:31,199 --> 00:01:32,359
Really?

21
00:01:33,501 --> 00:01:36,527
There are only 200
resident Brits in Panama.

22
00:01:37,538 --> 00:01:39,802
Butyou can surely ferret
out one or two...

23
00:01:40,008 --> 00:01:43,774
...who can gain you access
to the corridors ofpower.

24
00:01:58,192 --> 00:02:02,094
Look, look!
The Bridge of the Americas.

25
00:02:02,930 --> 00:02:07,958
You know, eversince
the canal cut them in half...

26
00:02:08,169 --> 00:02:10,467
...this bridge is now the only link...

27
00:02:10,672 --> 00:02:13,573
...between North and South America.

28
00:02:14,942 --> 00:02:16,239
Think about it!

29
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:50,469
The way l see it,
we all have a dream of ourselves...

30
00:02:51,179 --> 00:02:53,477
...that we could be more than we are.

31
00:02:53,848 --> 00:02:57,443
Well, Pendel and Braithwaite are here
to help you realize that dream...

32
00:02:57,652 --> 00:02:59,847
...in the Savile Row tradition.

33
00:03:01,055 --> 00:03:02,750
Let's try this one now.

34
00:03:05,660 --> 00:03:09,289
Oh, yeah, l guess this is kind of....

35
00:03:09,931 --> 00:03:13,799
l thought you'd like that one, sir.
Mr. Connery's choice.

36
00:03:14,001 --> 00:03:17,368
As soon as l saw you l thought,
''Who does he remind me of?''

37
00:03:17,572 --> 00:03:21,975
And that's it. ln the build too.
Golfer's shoulders.

38
00:04:57,071 --> 00:04:59,096
How about that, Uncle Benny?

39
00:04:59,307 --> 00:05:02,970
You've got the fluence, Harry.
l've always said it, and you have.

40
00:05:03,177 --> 00:05:06,271
You're the outright best tailor
in the world. Barnone.

41
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:09,472
Steady on, Uncle Benny, steady on.

42
00:05:14,021 --> 00:05:15,750
Harry, come on.

43
00:05:15,990 --> 00:05:18,083
-l'm coming.
-All right.

44
00:05:18,492 --> 00:05:21,928
All right, you get in first, Sarah.
Don't forget your belt.

45
00:05:22,129 --> 00:05:23,323
-Sarah.
-l'm trying!

46
00:05:23,531 --> 00:05:24,520
Mark.

47
00:05:28,903 --> 00:05:30,564
Okay. Bye-bye.

48
00:05:53,728 --> 00:05:56,788
George, George, l saw you yesterday.

49
00:05:57,231 --> 00:06:00,029
All right, here you go then.
How's your old lady?

50
00:06:11,479 --> 00:06:12,537
Sarah, Sarah!

51
00:06:12,747 --> 00:06:14,112
Hi, Bella.

52
00:06:14,548 --> 00:06:16,641
Dad, give me a quarter.

53
00:06:17,952 --> 00:06:19,476
Have you learnt your poem?

54
00:06:19,687 --> 00:06:22,986
Tyger, tyger, burning bright
ln the forest of the night

55
00:06:39,874 --> 00:06:41,307
-See you, Dad.
-Shalom.

56
00:06:41,509 --> 00:06:42,737
Shalom.

57
00:07:01,329 --> 00:07:02,591
Look at your hair!

58
00:07:02,797 --> 00:07:06,699
Oh, what immortal hand or eye
Could frame thy fearful cemetery

59
00:07:06,901 --> 00:07:09,165
No, ''symmetry.'' Symmetry.

60
00:07:09,370 --> 00:07:11,895
l still don't know what it means.

61
00:07:16,210 --> 00:07:18,576
-Did you see the news last night?
-Yes, l did.

62
00:07:18,779 --> 00:07:20,974
Your people want their canal back.

63
00:07:21,182 --> 00:07:24,618
Not my people, Ernesto.
They're rabid, right-wing senators.

64
00:07:24,819 --> 00:07:26,753
-Do you know what they are?
-Say it.

65
00:07:26,954 --> 00:07:28,421
Assholes.

66
00:07:52,780 --> 00:07:53,974
You see?

67
00:07:54,181 --> 00:07:55,614
Turn around.

68
00:07:57,518 --> 00:07:59,076
lt's only a tad, Ramon.

69
00:07:59,420 --> 00:08:03,186
lf you want to look good in my suit,
lose weight and grow a foot.

70
00:08:03,391 --> 00:08:05,951
Come to the shop.
We can ease it a little.

71
00:08:06,160 --> 00:08:07,388
Okay.

72
00:08:08,095 --> 00:08:12,156
So, what are we gonna do
about the overdraft, Harry?

73
00:08:12,867 --> 00:08:14,164
You tell me, Ramon.

74
00:08:14,368 --> 00:08:17,462
You have to think
about selling the farm, Harry.

75
00:08:17,671 --> 00:08:19,036
Sell it?

76
00:08:19,673 --> 00:08:21,436
lt's a gold mine, Ramon.

77
00:08:21,642 --> 00:08:26,011
Angelo's turning it around. He's a
very good man, Ramon. Dedicated.

78
00:08:26,547 --> 00:08:28,310
l hear you got a water problem.

79
00:08:28,849 --> 00:08:31,215
Did have, Ramon, did have.
l put that right.

80
00:08:31,419 --> 00:08:33,250
Now, it flows like....

81
00:08:33,454 --> 00:08:34,785
Water.

82
00:08:35,256 --> 00:08:36,382
Exactly, Ramon.

83
00:08:36,991 --> 00:08:40,188
Maybe you shouldn't have
bought it, eh?

84
00:08:40,394 --> 00:08:43,557
On your advice, Ramon. Fair's fair.

85
00:08:45,132 --> 00:08:47,566
The bank wishes to see
a substantial reduction...

86
00:08:47,768 --> 00:08:51,568
...on the outstanding sum
by the end of next month.

87
00:08:51,772 --> 00:08:53,296
Otherwise...

88
00:08:54,341 --> 00:08:55,706
...we have to call it in.

89
00:08:55,910 --> 00:08:56,899
What?

90
00:08:57,111 --> 00:08:58,305
The whole lot?

91
00:08:58,512 --> 00:09:00,571
But of course the whole lot.

92
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:07,084
You are my friend. l hate
to do this, but my hands are tied.

93
00:09:07,288 --> 00:09:08,380
What can l say?

94
00:09:09,123 --> 00:09:13,150
What am l going to tell Louisa?
l bought it with her inheritance.

95
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:16,261
Well, you're the storyteller, Harry.

96
00:09:31,512 --> 00:09:33,104
You're an angel.

97
00:09:40,788 --> 00:09:41,846
Someone to see you.

98
00:09:42,056 --> 00:09:43,045
Oh, yes? Who?

99
00:09:43,257 --> 00:09:45,122
New customer, he say.

100
00:09:45,426 --> 00:09:48,293
Hi. Name's Osnard.

101
00:09:48,929 --> 00:09:50,988
l phoned.

102
00:09:51,465 --> 00:09:53,763
Mr. Osnard. Harry Pendel.

103
00:09:54,435 --> 00:09:56,232
Very happy to meet you, sir.

104
00:09:57,037 --> 00:09:59,938
No offense, but l was hoping
to see Mr. Braithwaite.

105
00:10:00,508 --> 00:10:02,976
No chance of that,
l'm sorry to say, sir.

106
00:10:03,177 --> 00:10:06,408
My late partner has been dead
and gone these many years.

107
00:10:06,614 --> 00:10:10,209
Though his exacting standards
are very much alive and well.

108
00:10:10,417 --> 00:10:12,009
Glad to hear that.

109
00:10:13,154 --> 00:10:15,418
He dressed my father, you know.

110
00:10:15,623 --> 00:10:17,591
Back in his Savile Row days.

111
00:10:18,058 --> 00:10:21,459
Well, l never! Now that's a first,
l don't mind admitting.

112
00:10:21,662 --> 00:10:24,222
Father to son,
Savile Row to Panama City.

113
00:10:24,431 --> 00:10:27,195
-Did you hear that?
-l thought you'd be surprised.

114
00:10:27,401 --> 00:10:29,130
Surprised, sir, and delighted.

115
00:10:29,336 --> 00:10:32,066
Marta, put Mr. Osnard down
as an old customer.

116
00:10:32,273 --> 00:10:35,208
Arthur Braithwaite made
for his father.

117
00:10:35,409 --> 00:10:38,139
Now, if you'd care
to come this way, Mr. Osnard.

118
00:10:39,580 --> 00:10:41,309
What in hell happened to her?

119
00:10:42,283 --> 00:10:45,980
ln the bad old days, would that be?
Noriega's time?

120
00:10:46,187 --> 00:10:47,814
Rough justice meted out?

121
00:10:49,023 --> 00:10:51,651
-lf you'd care to take a seat, sir.
-Thank you.

122
00:10:53,294 --> 00:10:57,230
We call this The Club Room. Many of
our gentlemen spend time here...

123
00:10:57,431 --> 00:10:59,490
...in the lunch hour
and at the day's end.

124
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:00,928
And why not?

125
00:11:01,135 --> 00:11:03,433
What did you have in mind,
sir, exactly?

126
00:11:03,637 --> 00:11:07,073
l thought l'd start with a few
lounge suits. See how they go.

127
00:11:07,274 --> 00:11:11,973
After that, well, the ''full monty,''
as old Braithwaite used to say.

128
00:11:12,179 --> 00:11:13,942
l see. Very good, sir.

129
00:11:14,148 --> 00:11:18,050
Pity the expression's been hijacked.
Means quite the other thing now.

130
00:11:18,252 --> 00:11:21,050
-So they tell me, sir.
-Bollock naked, in fact.

131
00:11:21,255 --> 00:11:23,189
-Quite so, sir.
-Money's no problem.

132
00:11:24,191 --> 00:11:27,092
Take a look at these, sir.
See what takes your fancy.

133
00:11:27,595 --> 00:11:30,860
They're all the right weight
for this diabolical climate.

134
00:11:31,065 --> 00:11:34,000
Seven ounces of nicely breathing,
finest worsted.

135
00:11:34,201 --> 00:11:36,635
About all a man could
or should put up with.

136
00:11:36,837 --> 00:11:39,738
How about this one?
Alpaca, am l right?

137
00:11:39,940 --> 00:11:41,601
-Very good, sir.
-Perfect.

138
00:11:41,809 --> 00:11:43,800
And exactly what l should've picked.

139
00:11:44,011 --> 00:11:45,706
Given that money's no object?

140
00:11:48,015 --> 00:11:51,451
-So, what's next?
-Ah! The sun!

141
00:11:51,652 --> 00:11:53,745
Vital statistics.
Please step this way.

142
00:11:53,954 --> 00:11:55,319
Certainly.

143
00:11:55,589 --> 00:11:58,956
lf l could ask you to slip off
your jacket. Thank you, sir.

144
00:12:12,406 --> 00:12:15,170
You were Noriega's tailor,
weren't you, in his time?

145
00:12:15,709 --> 00:12:17,836
l'm sorry, sir, is that a problem?

146
00:12:18,045 --> 00:12:21,879
Not necessarily.
Smelly little bugger, was he?

147
00:12:22,850 --> 00:12:24,340
lf l may, sir.

148
00:12:26,020 --> 00:12:27,248
Forty.

149
00:12:27,454 --> 00:12:29,046
And the waist....

150
00:12:29,256 --> 00:12:30,689
What's the damage?

151
00:12:30,891 --> 00:12:33,189
A very creditable 34-plus.

152
00:12:33,527 --> 00:12:34,516
Plus what?

153
00:12:34,962 --> 00:12:36,793
Plus lunch, put it that way, sir.

154
00:12:38,132 --> 00:12:39,429
Very good.

155
00:12:39,633 --> 00:12:43,228
Do you ever miss it?
The old country? Savile Row?

156
00:12:44,471 --> 00:12:46,871
The Row. Well, now...

157
00:12:47,074 --> 00:12:48,598
...l do and l don't.

158
00:12:49,410 --> 00:12:51,810
Nothing beats it,
but when l was there...

159
00:12:52,012 --> 00:12:55,675
...l always felt very much
in old Arthur Braithwaite's shadow.

160
00:12:56,116 --> 00:13:00,280
Though it was Arthur Braithwaite
who encouraged me to spread my wings.

161
00:13:00,487 --> 00:13:04,389
-Good old boy, Arthur, was he?
-One of the old school, sir.

162
00:13:07,795 --> 00:13:09,319
Now, if l might....

163
00:13:10,898 --> 00:13:12,229
Very good, sir.

164
00:13:12,966 --> 00:13:14,399
Do we dress right or left?

165
00:13:14,601 --> 00:13:18,264
Most gentlemen favor left these days.
Don't think it's political.

166
00:13:18,472 --> 00:13:22,465
Never know where the bloody thing is.
Bobs about like a windsock.

167
00:13:23,177 --> 00:13:25,145
-You were saying?
-Saying, sir?

168
00:13:25,346 --> 00:13:29,248
Braithwaite. Telling you
to spread your wings.

169
00:13:29,683 --> 00:13:32,652
Yes, of course.
l remember it like yesterday.

170
00:13:32,853 --> 00:13:36,516
l was cutting a nice muted check
hacking jacket for Lord Braeburn.

171
00:13:36,724 --> 00:13:39,318
Finest mohair, dash of cashmere.

172
00:13:39,760 --> 00:13:42,786
l looked up and he was looking
at me from the doorway.

173
00:13:43,130 --> 00:13:44,927
Arthur Braithwaite, that is.

174
00:13:45,132 --> 00:13:47,692
He was a big man, imposing.

175
00:13:47,901 --> 00:13:50,631
He had a presence.
lt's hard to put it into words.

176
00:13:50,838 --> 00:13:52,635
-lt was the moustache.
-Moustache?

177
00:13:52,840 --> 00:13:55,172
Bloody great bushy job,
soup all over it.

178
00:13:55,809 --> 00:13:59,472
-There was no moustache in my day.
-l can see it now. Bright brown.

179
00:13:59,680 --> 00:14:03,081
l think we're being rumbled, Harry.
Admit nothing. Deny all.

180
00:14:03,283 --> 00:14:05,251
l think your memory's playing tricks.

181
00:14:05,452 --> 00:14:09,650
You're thinking of another man and
awarding his moustache to Braithwaite.

182
00:14:11,358 --> 00:14:12,723
Go on.

183
00:14:12,926 --> 00:14:17,056
''Harry,'' he says to me,
''l think you've earned your spurs.

184
00:14:17,264 --> 00:14:19,425
How would you feel
about taking my name...

185
00:14:19,633 --> 00:14:22,101
...and tradition to the New World?

186
00:14:22,302 --> 00:14:24,668
l'm talking about a full partnership.''

187
00:14:24,872 --> 00:14:27,705
l don't mind saying,
there were tears in my eyes.

188
00:14:27,908 --> 00:14:30,206
You've practically got tears in mine.

189
00:14:30,711 --> 00:14:31,803
Thank you, sir.

190
00:14:32,579 --> 00:14:35,912
l've never heard such a load
of bullshit in my life.

191
00:14:38,519 --> 00:14:40,282
Come and sit down, Harry.

192
00:14:40,621 --> 00:14:41,815
lt's all right.

193
00:14:42,089 --> 00:14:44,319
l'm your fairy godmother.

194
00:14:44,958 --> 00:14:48,450
The thing is, Harry,
l know who you are.

195
00:14:48,962 --> 00:14:51,931
More accurately,
l know who you aren't.

196
00:14:52,132 --> 00:14:55,329
-l don't know what you're saying.
-lt's all right. Relax.

197
00:14:55,536 --> 00:14:59,063
Because l know. You're 90601 7 Pendel.

198
00:14:59,273 --> 00:15:01,673
Six years for arson,
served two and a half.

199
00:15:01,875 --> 00:15:05,834
Learnt your tailoring in the slammer.
lnsurance scam, wasn't it?

200
00:15:06,046 --> 00:15:08,480
Set fire to a warehouse
for your Uncle Benny.

201
00:15:08,682 --> 00:15:11,173
They caught you
with the matches in your hand.

202
00:15:11,385 --> 00:15:13,216
You've never been near Savile Row.

203
00:15:13,420 --> 00:15:15,217
Braithwaite is your Uncle Benny...

204
00:15:15,422 --> 00:15:19,051
...raised from the dead, born again
and given a size-nine halo.

205
00:15:22,963 --> 00:15:26,797
Upon release, you did a runner to
Panama with your Uncle Benny's help.

206
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:28,865
Built up a fine business.

207
00:15:29,069 --> 00:15:33,096
Married the daughter of an American
canal engineer. Well-respected man.

208
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:37,041
But you owe the bank 50,000,
thanks to that farm.

209
00:15:37,244 --> 00:15:39,735
You've put in the shop
and the house as collateral.

210
00:15:39,947 --> 00:15:42,507
Not wise, Harry. Not wise at all.

211
00:15:43,484 --> 00:15:46,282
l can almost hear the creditors
banging on the door.

212
00:15:46,620 --> 00:15:47,746
Who are you?

213
00:15:48,088 --> 00:15:49,715
l'm Andy Osnard.

214
00:15:49,923 --> 00:15:53,222
New boy at the British Embassy,
finding my way around town.

215
00:16:01,435 --> 00:16:03,369
Strictly between us...

216
00:16:03,637 --> 00:16:06,128
...l'm Ml.6's man in Panama.

217
00:16:06,507 --> 00:16:09,567
lt's dark and lonely work,
like oral sex.

218
00:16:09,776 --> 00:16:11,767
But someone has to do it, Harry.

219
00:16:13,146 --> 00:16:16,479
l'm opening up a little network.
Keeping an eye on the canal.

220
00:16:16,884 --> 00:16:19,148
So, what's that got to do with me?

221
00:16:19,353 --> 00:16:21,446
What gives you
the right to come here...

222
00:16:21,655 --> 00:16:25,318
...sandbag me with my past
after l've paid my debt to society?

223
00:16:26,026 --> 00:16:28,290
Cool down. l'm bonus.

224
00:16:30,397 --> 00:16:31,625
Okay.

225
00:16:31,932 --> 00:16:32,921
What do you want?

226
00:16:34,034 --> 00:16:35,365
Your memory.

227
00:16:35,636 --> 00:16:37,035
Your ''rock of eye.''

228
00:16:37,237 --> 00:16:41,230
lsn't that the expression? Things you
know and don't even know you know.

229
00:16:41,441 --> 00:16:43,500
Highest prices paid.

230
00:16:46,680 --> 00:16:48,307
Get out. Now.

231
00:16:48,682 --> 00:16:49,876
Off.

232
00:16:50,183 --> 00:16:53,448
Don't be a cunt, Harry.
We're made for each other.

233
00:16:53,654 --> 00:16:56,782
You have debts, l have money.
Where's your patriotism?

234
00:16:57,057 --> 00:16:59,787
l had it out in prison,
without an anesthetic.

235
00:17:06,833 --> 00:17:10,200
There's five grand there.
Say it's on account of the suits.

236
00:17:10,404 --> 00:17:14,602
Call it ''entertainment expenses,''
anything you like, really.

237
00:17:14,808 --> 00:17:16,935
l want us to get on, Harry.

238
00:17:17,477 --> 00:17:18,535
Go on.

239
00:17:22,249 --> 00:17:24,240
Show me around, is all.

240
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:27,680
Do l have a choice?

241
00:17:27,888 --> 00:17:29,947
Oh, don't put it like that.

242
00:17:30,157 --> 00:17:33,684
lt's a game. Let's have some fun, eh?

243
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:40,858
Hi.

244
00:17:41,602 --> 00:17:43,467
No, nothing much.

245
00:17:44,571 --> 00:17:47,472
Well, sure, if you feel you have to.

246
00:17:48,041 --> 00:17:52,102
-Why not just bring him home?
-l think l'll take him to the club.

247
00:17:53,080 --> 00:17:55,378
Not sure. He's an odd chap.

248
00:17:56,450 --> 00:17:57,849
No, nothing's wrong.

249
00:17:58,151 --> 00:18:00,142
Your voice sounds funny.

250
00:18:05,025 --> 00:18:07,255
He called it a windsock?

251
00:18:18,872 --> 00:18:21,636
Señor. Good evening, Mr. Pendel.

252
00:18:22,876 --> 00:18:26,334
-Must have cost a lot to get in here.
-Had to be done.

253
00:18:26,546 --> 00:18:29,606
Hey, Harry, what about my blazer?

254
00:18:29,883 --> 00:18:33,649
Drop by on Tuesday, Luis.
lt'll be ready to try on.

255
00:18:34,454 --> 00:18:36,786
Blazers, they all want blazers.

256
00:18:36,990 --> 00:18:38,651
You dress everyone here?

257
00:18:38,859 --> 00:18:40,156
Just about, Andy.

258
00:18:40,360 --> 00:18:41,884
So who are ''they''?

259
00:18:42,095 --> 00:18:43,756
Who gets to join?

260
00:18:43,964 --> 00:18:47,559
Basically, 30 ruling families,
their lawyers and their bankers.

261
00:18:47,768 --> 00:18:49,793
And their tailors, l take it.

262
00:18:50,570 --> 00:18:53,334
When the Americans took out
Noriega, l said to myself:

263
00:18:53,540 --> 00:18:57,374
''Harry, they got Ali Baba,
but they missed the 40 thieves.''

264
00:18:57,811 --> 00:18:59,073
Well, here they are.

265
00:18:59,279 --> 00:19:01,179
So fill me in.

266
00:19:01,381 --> 00:19:04,145
Nobody ever loses
their reputation in Panama.

267
00:19:04,351 --> 00:19:07,616
They hang it in the closet
for a bit to get its shape back.

268
00:19:07,821 --> 00:19:10,756
When they put it on again,
it's as good as new.

269
00:19:11,725 --> 00:19:13,716
On the dance floor, Rafi Domingo.

270
00:19:13,927 --> 00:19:16,555
Shipping and drugs.

271
00:19:18,065 --> 00:19:19,692
l could fuck that very easily.

272
00:19:23,236 --> 00:19:26,296
-Wouldn't be any pain at all.
-A lot have, Andy.

273
00:19:26,506 --> 00:19:28,497
A lot wish they had, who haven't...

274
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:32,076
...and one or two have,
who wish they hadn't.

275
00:19:36,249 --> 00:19:38,114
Who are those charmers just come in?

276
00:19:38,585 --> 00:19:41,452
Government ministers
and the money boys who own them.

277
00:19:42,122 --> 00:19:45,558
At the table, bunch of gentlemen
from the loyal opposition.

278
00:19:45,759 --> 00:19:48,125
They come much cheaper, naturally.

279
00:19:54,868 --> 00:19:56,733
Welcome to Panama.

280
00:19:57,571 --> 00:20:00,301
A Casablanca without heroes.

281
00:20:00,540 --> 00:20:02,303
You are pure gold, Harry.

282
00:20:02,642 --> 00:20:03,836
Hey!

283
00:20:04,044 --> 00:20:06,478
Harry!

284
00:20:07,714 --> 00:20:08,874
Mickie.

285
00:20:12,219 --> 00:20:13,208
Harry.

286
00:20:13,420 --> 00:20:16,651
Mickie, l think you're
a touch refreshed!

287
00:20:16,957 --> 00:20:18,447
Please, come and sit down.

288
00:20:18,658 --> 00:20:21,092
''A man should stand on his feet.''

289
00:20:22,195 --> 00:20:23,685
Anyone remember that?!

290
00:20:26,333 --> 00:20:27,960
lsn't that the next bit?

291
00:20:28,468 --> 00:20:32,871
''Never on our knees.'' Right.
Or on our asses.

292
00:20:33,073 --> 00:20:37,203
-So who the fuck are you, my friend?
-l'd like you to meet Andy Osnard.

293
00:20:37,410 --> 00:20:38,843
British Embassy.

294
00:20:39,045 --> 00:20:41,343
Mickie really is a genuine hero, Andy.

295
00:20:41,548 --> 00:20:44,711
One of the few with the guts
to stand up to you-know-who.

296
00:20:44,918 --> 00:20:47,478
Mickie, please sit down.
People are staring.

297
00:20:47,687 --> 00:20:50,451
l don't give a fuck about these fucks.

298
00:20:50,657 --> 00:20:54,388
These are the fucks who kept
that fuck Noriega in power.

299
00:20:54,594 --> 00:20:57,085
You know what l would do--
Mr. Andy, right?

300
00:20:57,297 --> 00:20:59,788
You know what l would do
if l was president?

301
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:03,265
-What?
-l'd kill every fuck in this room.

302
00:21:03,470 --> 00:21:04,767
All of us.

303
00:21:04,971 --> 00:21:07,633
Look at us. Look at us!

304
00:21:09,743 --> 00:21:13,144
We got everything
God needed to make paradise.

305
00:21:13,346 --> 00:21:14,404
And what do we do?

306
00:21:14,614 --> 00:21:16,673
We sell each other.

307
00:21:16,883 --> 00:21:19,477
We sell our country.
We sell it all away!

308
00:21:19,686 --> 00:21:21,586
Harry, you take him for a walk.

309
00:21:21,788 --> 00:21:23,653
Look at these people, eh!

310
00:21:24,257 --> 00:21:25,588
Look at these people.

311
00:21:25,826 --> 00:21:29,387
You sold your souls,
you don't even know it. Stupid!

312
00:21:30,931 --> 00:21:34,799
lf you make any more trouble,
l will never cut you another suit.

313
00:21:36,970 --> 00:21:39,905
Come on. l'll take you home.

314
00:21:40,874 --> 00:21:43,138
Sorry. He's an old friend,
you know.

315
00:21:45,879 --> 00:21:47,176
Hello, Harry.

316
00:21:47,447 --> 00:21:49,278
Señor Delgado. Buenos noches.

317
00:21:49,482 --> 00:21:51,950
Canal Commissioner?
He as clean as they say?

318
00:21:52,152 --> 00:21:54,017
Well, my wife thinks so.

319
00:21:54,754 --> 00:21:56,722
Come on, Mickie, what is this?

320
00:23:11,598 --> 00:23:12,997
Come on, Mickie.

321
00:23:14,200 --> 00:23:16,361
You're a good man, Harry.

322
00:23:16,569 --> 00:23:20,505
The only good men left in Panama City
are you and me.

323
00:23:20,707 --> 00:23:23,972
-That's all. You and me.
-Okay, in you go. Come on.

324
00:23:27,280 --> 00:23:29,771
He has heart, Mr. Cool.

325
00:23:29,983 --> 00:23:30,972
Heart.

326
00:23:31,184 --> 00:23:33,448
Come on, now. Call it a night.

327
00:23:47,801 --> 00:23:49,462
So, what's the story with him?

328
00:23:50,236 --> 00:23:51,430
Mickie?

329
00:23:52,806 --> 00:23:55,138
He was my first customer.

330
00:23:55,342 --> 00:23:56,900
Best-looking man in Panama.

331
00:23:58,178 --> 00:23:59,236
A god.

332
00:24:00,180 --> 00:24:02,944
Till Noriega threw him
into prison to shut him up.

333
00:24:03,416 --> 00:24:05,213
Didn't bloody well work, did it?

334
00:24:07,687 --> 00:24:10,383
There's more to Mickie Abraxas
than meets the eye.

335
00:24:10,857 --> 00:24:12,757
Oh, l'm sure there is.

336
00:24:13,727 --> 00:24:16,628
My people don't care
about the glorious past exploits...

337
00:24:16,830 --> 00:24:18,923
...of some shagged-out old wino.

338
00:24:19,132 --> 00:24:22,329
They want the real stuff.
Today's men.

339
00:24:22,936 --> 00:24:24,631
Tomorrow's, not yesterday's.

340
00:24:25,905 --> 00:24:28,339
We're not a fucking charity
for losers.

341
00:24:31,211 --> 00:24:33,441
l hope l haven't made
a mistake with you.

342
00:24:41,621 --> 00:24:44,283
Don't underestimate Mickie Abraxas.

343
00:24:44,491 --> 00:24:45,958
So?

344
00:24:46,159 --> 00:24:48,684
What if l was to tell you
he's still at it?

345
00:24:49,829 --> 00:24:51,592
At what, exactly?

346
00:24:51,965 --> 00:24:53,592
He's still in there.

347
00:24:54,234 --> 00:24:55,792
The Silent Opposition.

348
00:24:56,136 --> 00:24:58,366
The ''Silent Opposition''?

349
00:24:58,571 --> 00:25:01,631
He's never lost touch
with ordinary, decent people.

350
00:25:01,841 --> 00:25:03,433
Deprived people.

351
00:25:04,077 --> 00:25:07,513
People who are tired
of the corruption, the greed.

352
00:25:08,048 --> 00:25:10,209
Do you know what the poor call those?

353
00:25:12,919 --> 00:25:14,477
''The Cocaine Towers.''

354
00:25:14,687 --> 00:25:16,552
And our 85 banks?

355
00:25:16,756 --> 00:25:18,348
''The launderettes.''

356
00:25:19,259 --> 00:25:20,317
Can we buy him?

357
00:25:20,527 --> 00:25:22,552
Mickie? Never.

358
00:25:24,264 --> 00:25:27,631
But he might allow you
to contribute to the cause.

359
00:25:35,708 --> 00:25:39,872
Uncle Benny, l fill up. l can't stop.
l get the wind in my ears.

360
00:25:40,080 --> 00:25:43,106
You've got the fluence in full flow
and the rock of eye.

361
00:25:43,316 --> 00:25:46,877
But it's a curse
as well as a blessing.

362
00:26:03,703 --> 00:26:05,227
How'd it go?

363
00:26:09,943 --> 00:26:12,377
Fine. l think.

364
00:26:12,579 --> 00:26:13,807
Hey...

365
00:26:15,148 --> 00:26:16,672
...get in here.

366
00:26:27,794 --> 00:26:29,022
Hi.

367
00:26:30,029 --> 00:26:31,360
l missed you.

368
00:26:32,298 --> 00:26:35,199
Wait, l'll take my socks off.

369
00:26:36,603 --> 00:26:38,468
l may be some time.

370
00:27:15,108 --> 00:27:17,099
Mr. Osnard.

371
00:27:17,377 --> 00:27:19,538
Ah, Andrew Osnard.

372
00:27:19,746 --> 00:27:23,182
Nigel Stormont. Francesca Deane.

373
00:27:23,383 --> 00:27:25,044
-Hello.
-Welcome to Panama.

374
00:27:25,251 --> 00:27:26,775
Thank you, ambassador.

375
00:27:26,986 --> 00:27:27,953
Please.

376
00:27:28,154 --> 00:27:32,215
l gather you've been having
a look round already...

377
00:27:32,425 --> 00:27:33,392
...quite extensively.

378
00:27:33,593 --> 00:27:35,584
Yes, indeed. Great spot.

379
00:27:35,795 --> 00:27:37,023
Right up my street.

380
00:27:37,230 --> 00:27:42,031
And how should we describe your
street, Andrew...

381
00:27:42,235 --> 00:27:43,862
...to the curious?

382
00:27:44,470 --> 00:27:46,870
l usually say
l'm in information technology.

383
00:27:47,073 --> 00:27:49,769
Oh, you're one of them.

384
00:27:49,976 --> 00:27:51,136
''A friend.''

385
00:27:51,544 --> 00:27:54,672
That's right. l'm a friend.

386
00:27:55,548 --> 00:27:58,517
Oh, my dear, but it's a huge secret.

387
00:27:58,718 --> 00:28:01,312
Or it was, until Osnard blubbed it.

388
00:28:01,521 --> 00:28:04,786
l mean, l'm barely allowed to know it.

389
00:28:04,991 --> 00:28:07,755
Not the Osnard got
drummed out of Madrid?

390
00:28:08,027 --> 00:28:09,585
Foreign minister's wife, wasn't it?

391
00:28:10,630 --> 00:28:13,827
Not his wife. Mistress.

392
00:28:14,033 --> 00:28:16,297
There are some things
l won't do for England.

393
00:28:17,036 --> 00:28:19,470
Got your picture in the paper,
didn't it?

394
00:28:19,672 --> 00:28:22,197
Hence my posting to Panama.
What was your crime?

395
00:28:23,943 --> 00:28:24,910
Coffee?

396
00:28:25,111 --> 00:28:26,169
Thank you.

397
00:28:26,379 --> 00:28:27,903
Help yourself.

398
00:28:28,214 --> 00:28:31,445
ls it just exile, or do you
have a purpose here?

399
00:28:33,186 --> 00:28:34,312
Sure.

400
00:28:35,154 --> 00:28:38,715
The boys at home are concerned that
the world's biggest trade gateway...

401
00:28:38,925 --> 00:28:41,086
...doesn't fall into
the wrong hands...

402
00:28:43,963 --> 00:28:46,158
...now that it's in the wrong hands.

403
00:28:47,133 --> 00:28:50,227
Forgive me.
Don't want to seem presumptuous...

404
00:28:50,436 --> 00:28:52,961
...but l doubt you'll find
anything they don't know...

405
00:28:53,172 --> 00:28:55,766
...from our regular embassy briefings.

406
00:28:59,045 --> 00:29:01,275
Know about the Silent Opposition?

407
00:29:05,451 --> 00:29:06,850
There you go.

408
00:29:10,556 --> 00:29:12,353
You're a fast worker.

409
00:29:12,558 --> 00:29:15,755
See something worth having,
go after it.

410
00:29:15,962 --> 00:29:18,430
May l ask at what point we here
at the embassy...

411
00:29:18,631 --> 00:29:20,599
...will get sight of your product?

412
00:29:21,501 --> 00:29:24,470
My boss says no local sharing unless
he gives the nod...

413
00:29:24,671 --> 00:29:27,469
...but l'm not really bothered
about that.

414
00:29:28,207 --> 00:29:31,040
Say, the four of us in this room?

415
00:29:32,178 --> 00:29:34,169
l'd have no problem with that.

416
00:29:35,281 --> 00:29:39,445
Well, all that seems very
satisfactory. Nigel?

417
00:29:40,253 --> 00:29:41,686
Francesca?

418
00:29:42,455 --> 00:29:43,979
Good to have you with us, Andrew.

419
00:29:44,424 --> 00:29:46,119
Good to be here.

420
00:29:46,559 --> 00:29:49,221
Francesca will show you
to your office.

421
00:29:50,129 --> 00:29:51,289
Yes.

422
00:29:57,470 --> 00:29:59,961
lt's a bit on the poky side,
l'm afraid.

423
00:30:00,206 --> 00:30:02,606
Bit on the poky side's fine with me.

424
00:30:02,809 --> 00:30:05,073
We thought you'd be out
and about a lot.

425
00:30:05,278 --> 00:30:06,643
Here we are.

426
00:30:19,125 --> 00:30:20,820
What are you listening to?

427
00:30:24,597 --> 00:30:25,586
The sea.

428
00:30:31,938 --> 00:30:35,499
Bloody thing's been sitting in
the warehouse all its life.

429
00:30:36,976 --> 00:30:39,103
Stuck on one combo.

430
00:30:41,347 --> 00:30:42,974
Tumblers all shot.

431
00:30:48,454 --> 00:30:49,751
Gotcha!

432
00:30:54,394 --> 00:30:57,522
Are you quite sure that it
was locked in the first place?

433
00:31:02,135 --> 00:31:06,231
l'm staying at the Gamboa Rain Forest
Resort till the apartment's ready.

434
00:31:06,439 --> 00:31:07,997
Come out on Sunday.

435
00:31:08,207 --> 00:31:11,802
Spot of lunch. Swim in the lake.

436
00:31:13,646 --> 00:31:14,840
See how it goes.

437
00:31:16,649 --> 00:31:18,844
l think l'm busy on Sunday.

438
00:31:19,051 --> 00:31:20,541
You're right.

439
00:31:21,587 --> 00:31:23,020
lt was open.

440
00:31:25,792 --> 00:31:27,692
Just tight from lack of use.

441
00:31:32,899 --> 00:31:35,094
The ambassador's asked me
to brief you...

442
00:31:35,301 --> 00:31:37,861
...in case there's anything you
don't already know.

443
00:31:44,677 --> 00:31:48,738
Noriega formed these so-called
''Dignity Battalions.''

444
00:31:48,948 --> 00:31:50,506
Dingbats.

445
00:31:50,716 --> 00:31:55,744
They were to beat the dignity out of
anyone remotely critical of Noriega.

446
00:31:57,190 --> 00:32:00,250
lt was Dr. Frankenstein,
George Bush...

447
00:32:00,460 --> 00:32:03,088
...who created this monster...

448
00:32:03,296 --> 00:32:05,025
...when he was head of the ClA.

449
00:32:05,231 --> 00:32:07,028
And when Noriega's...

450
00:32:07,233 --> 00:32:11,135
...drug running and brutality
got too much, even for the ClA...

451
00:32:11,337 --> 00:32:16,172
...it was George, now President Bush,
who decided to take him out.

452
00:32:17,043 --> 00:32:18,374
And just to make sure...

453
00:32:19,278 --> 00:32:22,304
...they fire-bombed a big chunk
of the old city.

454
00:32:25,117 --> 00:32:28,348
Sadly, that's where
the anti-Noriega rebels were.

455
00:32:28,554 --> 00:32:31,717
The handful that Noriega hadn't
banged up already.

456
00:32:32,725 --> 00:32:36,889
So no more opposition,
silent or otherwise.

457
00:32:37,497 --> 00:32:38,725
Burnt...

458
00:32:39,532 --> 00:32:41,124
...scattered...

459
00:32:42,768 --> 00:32:44,201
...fled.

460
00:32:47,807 --> 00:32:50,674
Or risen again from the ashes.

461
00:33:02,889 --> 00:33:06,791
Okay, okay, okay.
Everybody, here we go.

462
00:33:15,468 --> 00:33:16,867
Sorry.

463
00:33:32,151 --> 00:33:33,641
Mickie!

464
00:33:34,987 --> 00:33:36,318
Come in.

465
00:33:50,670 --> 00:33:54,766
Sorry about the other night.
l'm going through a bad patch.

466
00:33:54,974 --> 00:33:58,740
ls it money, Mickie? ls it?
Maybe l can help.

467
00:34:01,047 --> 00:34:02,241
You?

468
00:34:03,683 --> 00:34:06,243
You got worse debts than me.

469
00:34:07,253 --> 00:34:09,881
Mr. Farmer, huh?

470
00:34:14,527 --> 00:34:17,587
Do you still keep in touch,
you know...

471
00:34:17,797 --> 00:34:20,891
...with any of the students,
the fighters, from the old days?

472
00:34:21,100 --> 00:34:25,696
No, they're all lawyers now. Bankers.

473
00:34:26,606 --> 00:34:29,803
Haven't you heard?
We got a democracy.

474
00:34:30,009 --> 00:34:32,603
There's still a lot to fight for,
Mickie.

475
00:34:34,046 --> 00:34:36,674
l haven't got the stomach for it.

476
00:34:36,882 --> 00:34:39,942
l get the shakes when l see a cop.

477
00:34:41,554 --> 00:34:44,614
Unless l'm drunk,
and then l want to hit him.

478
00:34:45,024 --> 00:34:47,049
Either way....

479
00:34:47,627 --> 00:34:49,720
What about Marta's people?

480
00:34:50,262 --> 00:34:51,889
They loved you.

481
00:34:52,431 --> 00:34:53,728
They looked up to you.

482
00:34:57,136 --> 00:34:59,400
You should give up on me, Harry.

483
00:35:00,473 --> 00:35:02,270
l'm a lost cause.

484
00:35:04,143 --> 00:35:05,872
How much do you owe, Mickie?

485
00:35:06,078 --> 00:35:08,569
Owe to the casino? To you?

486
00:35:08,781 --> 00:35:11,215
All of it. All in. Come on.

487
00:35:13,519 --> 00:35:16,784
Not much change out of 20 grand.

488
00:35:17,623 --> 00:35:19,215
l'll get it for you, Mickie.

489
00:35:19,792 --> 00:35:22,590
And l'm gonna make you a new suit.

490
00:35:23,129 --> 00:35:26,155
A lovely silk and mohair herringbone.

491
00:35:27,733 --> 00:35:29,030
Okay?

492
00:35:29,235 --> 00:35:31,897
Okay. Okay.

493
00:35:43,582 --> 00:35:45,607
-Señor Pendel?
-What have l done wrong, Marta?

494
00:35:45,818 --> 00:35:48,685
Nothing. That's the problem.
Look at these accounts.

495
00:35:48,888 --> 00:35:51,516
Your friend Rafi Domingo.
Two months overdue.

496
00:35:51,724 --> 00:35:54,215
Carry it till next month.
He's a good customer.

497
00:35:54,427 --> 00:35:57,487
He's a shit. He made all his
money under Noriega.

498
00:35:57,697 --> 00:35:59,164
l'm going to charge him interest.

499
00:35:59,365 --> 00:36:01,265
-You can't do that.
-Yes, l can.

500
00:36:01,467 --> 00:36:04,368
You're worried they won't like you
if you make them pay.

501
00:36:04,570 --> 00:36:05,730
lt's a tradition.

502
00:36:05,938 --> 00:36:08,236
Gentlemen keep tailors
waiting for money.

503
00:36:08,441 --> 00:36:11,433
