One picture's worth a thousand words.
Or a thousand bucks. Tell her that.

753
00:54:28,139 --> 00:54:29,003
-Tell her?
-Why not?

754
00:54:29,207 --> 00:54:31,698
Put her on the payroll.
Double your money.

755
00:54:32,010 --> 00:54:35,639
l want something in writing on
Delgado's dealings with the Chinese.

756
00:54:35,847 --> 00:54:37,007
No more bullshit.

757
00:54:37,215 --> 00:54:39,809
Louisa would never betray Delgado.

758
00:54:40,018 --> 00:54:41,383
She worships the man.

759
00:54:42,854 --> 00:54:44,321
Does she know where you're at?

760
00:54:44,823 --> 00:54:46,017
Not an inkling.

761
00:54:47,058 --> 00:54:49,322
Ever tell her about your prison days?

762
00:54:49,527 --> 00:54:50,551
Not as such.

763
00:54:50,762 --> 00:54:52,286
Haul her in, Harry...

764
00:54:52,497 --> 00:54:55,864
...or l might have to tell her
about Harry Pendel, the criminal.

765
00:54:56,067 --> 00:54:57,830
You stay away from her.

766
00:55:02,273 --> 00:55:04,173
Okay, l'll handle it.

767
00:55:13,518 --> 00:55:15,713
You're rather tense tonight, Lou.

768
00:55:17,589 --> 00:55:20,387
Maybe because you're peering
over my shoulder again.

769
00:55:21,693 --> 00:55:24,093
Or maybe because l had a call
from Donna.

770
00:55:25,797 --> 00:55:26,627
Donna?

771
00:55:27,065 --> 00:55:28,225
Teddy's wife.

772
00:55:30,568 --> 00:55:33,696
She said you were seen coming
out of the Hotel Paraiso.

773
00:55:35,073 --> 00:55:39,601
l said, ''Harry's a tailor. He has
clients from all walks of life.''

774
00:55:41,045 --> 00:55:42,103
True.

775
00:55:42,380 --> 00:55:44,814
You'd never meet them
at the Hotel Paraiso.

776
00:55:45,416 --> 00:55:48,852
l had a fitting with Andy.
Andy Osnard.

777
00:55:49,053 --> 00:55:50,384
He's a bit eccentric.

778
00:55:51,522 --> 00:55:53,046
Are you seeing someone?

779
00:55:53,391 --> 00:55:54,483
Me?

780
00:55:58,830 --> 00:56:01,958
You stay out late
and you don't say where.

781
00:56:04,335 --> 00:56:07,771
You come at me like a lover and
then you don't touch me for weeks.

782
00:56:10,141 --> 00:56:11,665
What's going on, Harry?

783
00:56:12,677 --> 00:56:14,304
Who's getting the rest of you?

784
00:56:14,579 --> 00:56:17,013
Uncle Benny, l'm cornered.

785
00:56:17,415 --> 00:56:19,815
There's nothing for it
but to tell her the truth.

786
00:56:20,318 --> 00:56:21,842
She deserves the truth.

787
00:56:22,053 --> 00:56:24,544
Harry-boy, l've told you
time and again:

788
00:56:24,756 --> 00:56:28,419
A man who tells the truth is bound
to be found out sooner or later.

789
00:56:28,626 --> 00:56:31,151
Try sincerity, that's a virtue.

790
00:56:31,362 --> 00:56:34,024
But truth, it's an affliction.

791
00:56:34,232 --> 00:56:36,257
l swear to you on my life...

792
00:56:37,568 --> 00:56:38,967
...there's no other woman.

793
00:56:40,405 --> 00:56:43,499
Never has been. Never will be.

794
00:56:46,711 --> 00:56:47,837
Okay.

795
00:56:56,654 --> 00:56:58,053
Louisa?

796
00:57:42,800 --> 00:57:45,132
l'm a thief in my own home.

797
00:57:45,336 --> 00:57:48,601
But with best intentions.
With a good heart.

798
00:57:49,073 --> 00:57:51,667
For the family.
Like you did forme.

799
00:57:51,876 --> 00:57:53,002
That's true.

800
00:57:53,211 --> 00:57:55,338
You're the apple ofmy eye, Harry.

801
00:57:55,546 --> 00:57:59,107
Stay shtum, and l'll
always be there foryou.

802
00:58:00,885 --> 00:58:02,853
Harry. Harry!

803
00:58:07,158 --> 00:58:08,284
l couldn't sleep.

804
00:58:09,727 --> 00:58:13,026
What do you mean you couldn't sleep?
You were just out cold.

805
00:58:14,665 --> 00:58:16,724
Busy times at the shop, Lou.

806
00:58:17,668 --> 00:58:20,034
So who is this Andy Osnard?

807
00:58:20,638 --> 00:58:23,971
-Tell me about him.
-He's become a bit of a pal...

808
00:58:24,342 --> 00:58:25,309
...as such.

809
00:58:26,811 --> 00:58:28,745
l used to be your pal...

810
00:58:28,946 --> 00:58:30,243
...''as such.''

811
00:58:31,349 --> 00:58:32,941
l'd like to meet him.

812
00:58:33,151 --> 00:58:35,619
Why don't you invite him on Sunday?

813
00:58:36,554 --> 00:58:38,215
That's Sarah's birthday.

814
00:58:39,090 --> 00:58:40,148
Why not?

815
00:58:41,159 --> 00:58:42,990
l could look into it.

816
00:58:43,494 --> 00:58:45,962
lf you don't want to call him,
l'll call him.

817
00:58:47,765 --> 00:58:48,663
Good.

818
00:59:05,983 --> 00:59:08,315
--and this season's suits
are very thin...

819
00:59:08,519 --> 00:59:10,783
...and it's lined with Panama's
best fabric.

820
00:59:19,397 --> 00:59:20,557
Buchan.

821
00:59:20,832 --> 00:59:23,801
Lady Jane's. Twenty minutes.
That's two-zero minutes.

822
00:59:24,502 --> 00:59:25,764
Over and out.

823
01:00:11,949 --> 01:00:14,213
He's been waiting and complaining.

824
01:00:14,552 --> 01:00:19,046
Sorry, Teddy. Jacket's ready.
Just pop into the fitting room.

825
01:00:24,462 --> 01:00:26,259
Sorry, Jaime, l need this.

826
01:00:31,903 --> 01:00:33,461
ln you go, Teddy.

827
01:00:39,243 --> 01:00:41,370
Wow! Even better than l thought.

828
01:00:41,579 --> 01:00:44,013
You look like Bobby De Niro
in this jacket.

829
01:00:44,215 --> 01:00:47,412
Don't schmooze me, Harry.
What's going on?

830
01:00:47,618 --> 01:00:50,280
Little bird tells me
you paid off your overdraft.

831
01:00:50,488 --> 01:00:52,115
Business is good, Teddy.

832
01:00:52,323 --> 01:00:54,154
l smell a story.

833
01:00:54,358 --> 01:00:55,723
There's no story.

834
01:00:56,594 --> 01:00:58,687
You want me to make one up?

835
01:00:58,896 --> 01:01:01,023
Don't. Louisa reads
your gossip column.

836
01:01:01,232 --> 01:01:03,223
l don't want her to know
l owed money.

837
01:01:03,434 --> 01:01:05,265
Come clean.

838
01:01:05,836 --> 01:01:07,895
Probably won't run it.

839
01:01:08,406 --> 01:01:11,967
l'm like that. The more l know,
the less l print.

840
01:01:16,714 --> 01:01:19,046
You know l'll find out
what you're up to...

841
01:01:19,984 --> 01:01:21,212
...don't you?

842
01:01:48,112 --> 01:01:50,376
Well, l had absolutely no idea...

843
01:01:50,581 --> 01:01:52,674
...how delightful
Panama was gonna be.

844
01:01:52,883 --> 01:01:55,283
Yes, it's beautiful country.

845
01:01:56,120 --> 01:01:58,213
l was thinking about the people.

846
01:01:59,457 --> 01:02:02,893
Meant a lot to me,
being able to tag along today.

847
01:02:03,094 --> 01:02:05,722
lt's been a real pleasure
to have you along, Andy.

848
01:02:05,930 --> 01:02:07,158
Hasn't it, darling?

849
01:02:08,032 --> 01:02:10,091
Can we go and see the monkeys, Dad?

850
01:02:10,635 --> 01:02:11,829
There's a monkey island.

851
01:02:12,036 --> 01:02:14,004
-We bring bananas for them.
-Wonderful.

852
01:02:14,205 --> 01:02:16,935
-What's my birthday girl say?
-Can Andy come too?

853
01:02:17,141 --> 01:02:20,770
No, Andy needs to stay here
and keep Mommy company.

854
01:02:20,978 --> 01:02:22,377
You go with Dad.

855
01:02:31,289 --> 01:02:32,278
ln you go.

856
01:02:32,490 --> 01:02:34,185
Cast off, captain.

857
01:02:40,464 --> 01:02:41,897
So, Andy...

858
01:02:42,266 --> 01:02:45,235
...maybe you wouldn't mind
telling me what you're up to.

859
01:02:48,506 --> 01:02:49,530
Sorry?

860
01:02:49,807 --> 01:02:54,210
There's something between you and my
husband, l know it. l can feel it.

861
01:02:55,212 --> 01:02:59,308
Ever since he's met you, he's
a changed man. Sneaky and secretive.

862
01:03:02,620 --> 01:03:06,351
All of a sudden, l'm his enemy
and you're his friend.

863
01:03:09,126 --> 01:03:12,220
lf l didn't know him better,
l'd say you two were gay.

864
01:03:18,235 --> 01:03:20,169
Do you want it straight?

865
01:03:22,406 --> 01:03:23,532
Always.

866
01:03:23,908 --> 01:03:25,375
You'll keep it secret?

867
01:03:27,044 --> 01:03:28,033
lf l have to.

868
01:03:31,549 --> 01:03:35,212
And he's told you nothing?
Absolutely nothing?

869
01:03:35,753 --> 01:03:36,981
Zero.

870
01:03:38,222 --> 01:03:40,452
lnformation is my business. Gossip.

871
01:03:40,658 --> 01:03:42,250
Harry's kind of gossip.

872
01:03:42,460 --> 01:03:44,690
He's smart, he's down-to-earth.

873
01:03:44,895 --> 01:03:47,022
He's got great contacts and no agenda.

874
01:03:47,498 --> 01:03:49,625
Are you talking about spying?

875
01:03:50,234 --> 01:03:54,193
Oh, that's much too heavy a word
for what Harry's doing.

876
01:03:55,406 --> 01:03:59,365
-Are you paying him?
-No money, l'm afraid.

877
01:03:59,577 --> 01:04:01,943
Just the honor
and privilege of service.

878
01:04:04,482 --> 01:04:08,213
ls that why he's been looking
at all my private papers?

879
01:04:08,986 --> 01:04:11,147
Oh, no. Harry.

880
01:04:11,756 --> 01:04:12,950
Oh, bless him.

881
01:04:13,891 --> 01:04:16,257
That really is going too far.

882
01:04:18,162 --> 01:04:20,289
Spying on his own wife.

883
01:04:24,435 --> 01:04:25,766
l'm terribly sorry.

884
01:04:28,205 --> 01:04:31,368
Still, you are the canal, aren't you?

885
01:04:31,575 --> 01:04:34,544
You sit at Ernie Delgado's right hand.

886
01:04:35,079 --> 01:04:39,072
Harry's aware that we're desperate
to know what will become of it.

887
01:04:41,752 --> 01:04:44,619
The canal is always gonna run
the way it's run.

888
01:04:46,190 --> 01:04:48,420
Ernie Delgado will make sure of it.

889
01:04:48,626 --> 01:04:50,116
That's as may be...

890
01:04:51,362 --> 01:04:53,057
...but it's our main artery.

891
01:04:53,264 --> 01:04:56,290
You can't blame us if we need
constant reassurance.

892
01:04:59,003 --> 01:05:00,937
Harry's only trying to help.

893
01:05:02,840 --> 01:05:04,068
Don't...

894
01:05:05,776 --> 01:05:07,209
...use him.

895
01:05:08,946 --> 01:05:10,311
l love him.

896
01:05:11,348 --> 01:05:13,213
As we both do.

897
01:05:14,084 --> 01:05:15,608
l'm going for a swim.

898
01:05:18,189 --> 01:05:19,156
-There's one.
-Where?

899
01:05:19,356 --> 01:05:20,323
-Up there.
-Oh, yeah!

900
01:05:20,524 --> 01:05:22,321
Oh, he's lovely!

901
01:05:27,465 --> 01:05:28,727
So....

902
01:05:30,935 --> 01:05:34,234
Tell me,
how did Harry win your heart?

903
01:05:36,307 --> 01:05:38,605
l was raised in the canal...

904
01:05:38,876 --> 01:05:41,640
...around military types
and engineers like my father...

905
01:05:41,846 --> 01:05:44,212
...and l had never met anyone
like Harry.

906
01:05:44,415 --> 01:05:46,679
He treated me like a princess.

907
01:05:47,718 --> 01:05:49,413
Sent me flowers every day.

908
01:05:49,620 --> 01:05:51,087
Wrote me love letters.

909
01:05:51,288 --> 01:05:55,247
Did he have to get
Arthur Braithwaite's permission?

910
01:05:56,060 --> 01:06:00,258
He called him in London.
He was on his deathbed, the poor man.

911
01:06:00,464 --> 01:06:01,829
Oh, God.

912
01:06:03,534 --> 01:06:05,695
Did he fly over for the funeral?

913
01:06:06,470 --> 01:06:08,028
Arthur forbade it.

914
01:06:08,539 --> 01:06:11,997
Harry was completely wiped out.

915
01:06:12,543 --> 01:06:14,306
l'm sure he was.

916
01:06:24,221 --> 01:06:28,920
So the two of you have lived
happily ever after ever since?

917
01:06:31,428 --> 01:06:33,453
Yeah, until you came along.

918
01:06:35,966 --> 01:06:37,661
Don't you ever feel like...

919
01:06:38,569 --> 01:06:40,230
...breaking out?

920
01:06:42,940 --> 01:06:44,601
Running wild...

921
01:06:45,609 --> 01:06:47,634
...just for the badness?

922
01:06:50,881 --> 01:06:52,143
Never.

923
01:06:53,817 --> 01:06:55,808
Harry is my virtue.

924
01:06:57,788 --> 01:06:59,085
Without him...

925
01:07:01,592 --> 01:07:02,820
...l'd be....

926
01:07:03,027 --> 01:07:04,426
You'd be...

927
01:07:05,262 --> 01:07:07,856
...like Harry without
Arthur Braithwaite.

928
01:07:22,046 --> 01:07:24,446
Well, she's finally asleep.

929
01:07:26,550 --> 01:07:28,450
l think she enjoyed her day.

930
01:07:28,986 --> 01:07:30,578
Yeah, l think so too.

931
01:07:36,126 --> 01:07:37,457
And did you?

932
01:07:38,028 --> 01:07:40,519
Yeah. Kind of.

933
01:07:41,398 --> 01:07:43,730
What did you and Andy
find to talk about?

934
01:07:45,936 --> 01:07:47,369
You, mostly.

935
01:07:47,738 --> 01:07:49,933
Bit of a boring topic, wasn't it?

936
01:07:51,008 --> 01:07:54,967
You're a very surprising person,
Harry Pendel.

937
01:07:56,313 --> 01:07:58,577
After all these years?

938
01:07:59,717 --> 01:08:02,277
Just don't come between me
and Ernie Delgado.

939
01:08:02,720 --> 01:08:06,019
My work is off-limits.
Do you understand?

940
01:08:06,223 --> 01:08:08,555
Okay, Lou. Absolutely.

941
01:08:09,126 --> 01:08:10,320
Done.

942
01:08:20,304 --> 01:08:21,498
Harry.

943
01:08:22,306 --> 01:08:23,295
What?

944
01:08:24,441 --> 01:08:26,204
Make me laugh.

945
01:08:35,753 --> 01:08:38,187
-You've got a gift for it.
-What?

946
01:08:40,057 --> 01:08:41,217
Letting go.

947
01:08:42,393 --> 01:08:46,454
-Few people can.
-You can't, or won't.

948
01:08:47,231 --> 01:08:48,323
No.

949
01:08:48,966 --> 01:08:53,096
-l've been reading your files.
-Oh, those fucking files.

950
01:08:54,872 --> 01:08:57,306
We know too much about each other.

951
01:08:58,842 --> 01:09:00,776
Kills the romance.

952
01:09:01,278 --> 01:09:02,711
What romance?

953
01:09:03,447 --> 01:09:06,314
Oh, shit! Shit.

954
01:09:09,887 --> 01:09:10,945
Yes?

955
01:09:11,622 --> 01:09:13,681
Yeah. What?

956
01:09:15,059 --> 01:09:16,959
lt's a bit of a bad time, actually.

957
01:09:17,761 --> 01:09:20,093
l didn't know what she knew,
did l?

958
01:09:22,066 --> 01:09:24,933
Well, l'm sure you handled it
like a master.

959
01:09:25,969 --> 01:09:29,166
Look-- Hey, l had to think
on my feet, didn't l?

960
01:09:29,707 --> 01:09:31,038
All right.

961
01:09:31,842 --> 01:09:33,332
All right, if you must.

962
01:09:34,912 --> 01:09:36,504
Rendezvous number three.

963
01:09:37,848 --> 01:09:41,079
You know where that is, don't you?
Oh, good.

964
01:09:41,752 --> 01:09:43,720
Twenty-three hundred hours.
Good.

965
01:09:45,889 --> 01:09:49,347
What warrants dragging me out of
the saddle on a Sunday night, eh?

966
01:09:49,560 --> 01:09:50,549
Look, about Louisa.

967
01:09:50,761 --> 01:09:54,288
Some woman, Harry. l envy you.
The way she looks up to you.

968
01:09:54,498 --> 01:09:56,830
You're her moral virtue, her center.

969
01:09:57,034 --> 01:10:00,299
Just like Arthur Braithwaite
was to you, is what she said.

970
01:10:00,804 --> 01:10:02,169
l enjoyed the comparison.

971
01:10:02,372 --> 01:10:03,999
-You say anything?
-Would l ever?

972
01:10:04,208 --> 01:10:07,075
Expect me to tell her that
an old Jew brought me up?

973
01:10:07,277 --> 01:10:09,245
Burned his frocks as a favor?

974
01:10:09,446 --> 01:10:11,107
Hated the old fellow, did you?

975
01:10:11,315 --> 01:10:15,115
-l know this place where we can talk.
-l loved him. l revere him.

976
01:10:15,319 --> 01:10:18,686
Dressed him up as Arthur Braithwaite.
Gave him a good suit.

977
01:10:18,889 --> 01:10:21,380
''Clothes maketh the man,''
and all that.

978
01:10:51,922 --> 01:10:55,016
Come on, let's dance.
Camp it up a bit.

979
01:11:15,813 --> 01:11:17,940
Come on. l'll lead.

980
01:11:19,950 --> 01:11:23,442
So, l gather you've made
no attempt to recruit her so far.

981
01:11:23,654 --> 01:11:25,986
As of now, that is correct.

982
01:11:26,190 --> 01:11:28,283
Seemed perfectly approachable to me.

983
01:11:28,492 --> 01:11:31,723
-Thought l'd have a go at her myself.
-No, don't do that.

984
01:11:32,629 --> 01:11:35,154
ls this what you came to tell me?
Lay off her?

985
01:11:35,365 --> 01:11:37,663
l came to tell you
l've had enough.

986
01:11:38,001 --> 01:11:38,831
l want out.

987
01:11:39,036 --> 01:11:42,767
l don't think so. You've taken
the money, l want something for it.

988
01:11:43,407 --> 01:11:44,874
Those documents.

989
01:11:45,075 --> 01:11:47,669
Those ones that you snapped.
Did you read them?

990
01:11:47,878 --> 01:11:51,314
-l was pushed for time, Andy.
-Pension scheme for lock-keepers.

991
01:11:51,515 --> 01:11:54,348
Dredging contract.
Water analysis. Zilch.

992
01:11:54,551 --> 01:11:57,111
Time to deliver.
l'm tired of your bullshit.

993
01:11:57,321 --> 01:11:58,754
l can't go on with it!

994
01:11:59,456 --> 01:12:01,287
You want me to tell Louisa...

995
01:12:01,491 --> 01:12:03,288
...about Harry the convict?

996
01:12:07,831 --> 01:12:09,765
Will you tell me what you want?

997
01:12:10,133 --> 01:12:11,157
Come here.

998
01:12:11,702 --> 01:12:14,466
Keep moving. Stop acting so butch.

999
01:12:15,739 --> 01:12:20,176
lf the canal's being flogged off
on presidential instructions...

1000
01:12:20,377 --> 01:12:24,313
...what's the price? Who's the buyer?
When do they sign the contract?

1001
01:12:24,514 --> 01:12:28,280
How much are Delgado and the pres
creaming off for themselves?

1002
01:12:28,485 --> 01:12:29,952
-Right.
-Can't hear you.

1003
01:12:30,153 --> 01:12:32,314
-Right.
-Then there's your end of the bargain.

1004
01:12:32,522 --> 01:12:36,754
Abraxas, the Silent Opposition.
Are they going for direct action?

1005
01:12:36,960 --> 01:12:40,123
-Direct action being in this case?
-Shootibangs.

1006
01:12:40,330 --> 01:12:42,491
Raising proletarian consciousness.

1007
01:12:42,699 --> 01:12:45,463
Bombing banks, gunning down
a couple millionaires.

1008
01:12:45,669 --> 01:12:49,469
-No, not Mickie, not Marta.
-So, what the fuck are they doing?

1009
01:12:49,673 --> 01:12:53,439
Who are they buying arms from?
What are they gonna do with them?

1010
01:12:53,644 --> 01:12:56,408
They'll have to do more than
wear white shirts...

1011
01:12:56,613 --> 01:12:59,514
...and get the shit beaten
out of them by the dingbats!

1012
01:12:59,716 --> 01:13:01,616
-Come on.
-l've got to get out.

1013
01:13:01,818 --> 01:13:03,445
l can't think.

1014
01:13:04,054 --> 01:13:06,318
-l can't breathe.
-Go, Harry. Go, go, go.

1015
01:13:10,594 --> 01:13:13,188
Get me some answers.
Your ass is on the line.

1016
01:13:13,397 --> 01:13:16,161
London's coming.
Get the stuff, we make you rich.

1017
01:13:16,366 --> 01:13:19,767
You don't, we tell the Pans
you've been spying for the Yanks.

1018
01:13:19,970 --> 01:13:23,167
You and Louisa both.
Do you understand what l'm saying?

1019
01:13:32,582 --> 01:13:34,516
l haven't come clean with you.

1020
01:13:35,419 --> 01:13:37,319
l've been dragging my feet.

1021
01:13:37,688 --> 01:13:39,747
At Mickie's behest, l might add.

1022
01:13:40,824 --> 01:13:43,418
He has a huge arms shipment
on the way.

1023
01:13:43,627 --> 01:13:46,027
But he'll pay for it
from another source.

1024
01:13:46,229 --> 01:13:49,255
Oh, yeah? Who the fuck would that be?

1025
01:13:49,466 --> 01:13:50,797
Won't say.

1026
01:13:51,201 --> 01:13:53,101
No, he wouldn't, would he?

1027
01:13:53,303 --> 01:13:56,397
-How much?
-lt's big money, Andy.

1028
01:13:56,606 --> 01:13:59,632
''Harry,'' he says to me,
''your guys pay peanuts.

1029
01:13:59,843 --> 01:14:01,470
This is out of their league.''

1030
01:14:02,579 --> 01:14:03,705
Well...

1031
01:14:04,915 --> 01:14:07,679
...this is an interesting
development, Harry.

1032
01:14:08,318 --> 01:14:10,786
-Give me a ballpark figure.
-Ten.

1033
01:14:10,988 --> 01:14:13,684
We're talking
ten million dollars, Andy.

1034
01:14:13,890 --> 01:14:15,380
Ten million dollars?

1035
01:14:16,159 --> 01:14:17,148
Yeah.

1036
01:14:17,861 --> 01:14:20,455
Ten million dollars.

1037
01:14:23,266 --> 01:14:24,563
Yeah.

1038
01:14:33,944 --> 01:14:35,605
-Andrew.
-Sir.

1039
01:14:35,812 --> 01:14:38,042
The winds of fortune
blew me to Caracas...

1040
01:14:38,248 --> 01:14:41,740
...allowing me this brief stopover.
l'm on my way to Washington.

1041
01:14:41,952 --> 01:14:46,355
Our revered leader, Henry Cavendish,
is coming too. Pick up the phone.

1042
01:14:46,590 --> 01:14:48,490
There's prestige at stake, you see.

1043
01:14:48,692 --> 01:14:49,556
Oh, Andrew...

1044
01:14:50,460 --> 01:14:54,556
...l've come all this way to look
you in the eye and ask you this:

1045
01:14:54,765 --> 01:14:59,031
Can you back it up?
Are we copper-bottomed?

1046
01:15:00,404 --> 01:15:01,666
Yes.

1047
01:15:03,840 --> 01:15:07,276
-How much are they asking for?
-Fifteen million.

1048
01:15:07,811 --> 01:15:09,073
Fifteen.

1049
01:15:09,913 --> 01:15:12,711
lf l get it for you,
can you guarantee action?

1050
01:15:13,016 --> 01:15:14,381
Oh, absolutely.

1051
01:15:14,584 --> 01:15:16,051
Go after them, Andrew.

1052
01:15:16,253 --> 01:15:20,087
Push. The iron is hot.
Strike!

1053
01:15:24,094 --> 01:15:27,393
Sir, can l have your glass?
We are ready for landing.

1054
01:15:30,467 --> 01:15:31,661
Thank you.

1055
01:15:41,912 --> 01:15:44,642
Oh, Harry. l hear that Delgado...

1056
01:15:44,848 --> 01:15:47,908
...is setting up a canal
police force...

1057
01:15:48,118 --> 01:15:50,177
...with powers to search the ships.

1058
01:15:50,387 --> 01:15:55,723
lt'll never happen. lt would kill
the drug trade, the arms trade...

1059
01:15:55,959 --> 01:15:58,120
...everything we hold dear.

1060
01:15:58,528 --> 01:16:01,190
The way it is now,
you pay your dues...

1061
01:16:01,398 --> 01:16:04,993
...you don't piss in the locks,
they don't fuck with you.

1062
01:16:05,202 --> 01:16:08,467
Does Louisa know anything
about this little plan, Harry?

1063
01:16:08,672 --> 01:16:10,230
Leave Louisa out of this.

1064
01:16:10,440 --> 01:16:14,740
Take it easy, Harry.
Time you took some holiday.

1065
01:16:15,445 --> 01:16:18,846
-You look fucked out.
-Maybe if you paid your bill...

1066
01:16:19,049 --> 01:16:21,745
-...l might be able to.
-Maybe you'd be healthier...

1067
01:16:21,952 --> 01:16:23,681
...if you stuck to tailoring.

1068
01:16:23,954 --> 01:16:26,218
-Listen, Teddy--
-Hey, Harry.

1069
01:16:26,857 --> 01:16:28,347
lt doesn't look right.

1070
01:16:28,558 --> 01:16:30,719
This isn't a suit,
it's a piece of shit.

1071
01:16:32,329 --> 01:16:35,264
Come on, it's the first fitting.
lt can be fixed.

1072
01:16:35,465 --> 01:16:37,831
l don't know.
Think l'm gonna go to Armani.

1073
01:16:38,168 --> 01:16:40,159
Get myself a proper suit.

1074
01:16:42,873 --> 01:16:45,740
He doesn't like it when
l mention Armani.

1075
01:16:45,942 --> 01:16:48,035
Harry, why you make me this shit?

1076
01:16:48,245 --> 01:16:50,270
Why can't you make
a suit like Armani?

1077
01:16:50,480 --> 01:16:52,243
Why can't l make
a suit like Armani?

1078
01:16:55,118 --> 01:16:57,882
You think Armani can make
a suit like Harry Pendel?

1079
01:16:58,121 --> 01:16:59,383
Why not?

1080
01:16:59,789 --> 01:17:03,384
Okay, fuck off. Go down the road,
buy an Armani!

1081
01:17:03,593 --> 01:17:06,118
Save yourself $1 000,
see if l care!

1082
01:17:06,329 --> 01:17:09,264
At Pendel and Braithwaite
you get Savile Row tailoring...

1083
01:17:09,466 --> 01:17:11,593
...with 400 years of tradition
behind it.

1084
01:17:11,801 --> 01:17:14,463
Down the road you get an
ltalian gents' outfitter.

1085
01:17:14,671 --> 01:17:17,367
lf you don't understand,
then save your money.

1086
01:17:17,574 --> 01:17:18,939
Hey, Harry, come on.

1087
01:17:19,543 --> 01:17:22,478
The whole country's
going down the plug hole!

1088
01:17:22,679 --> 01:17:24,670
Nobody cares!

1089
01:17:24,881 --> 01:17:27,475
Someone's got to stand up
and be counted!

1090
01:17:27,684 --> 01:17:31,484
Someone has to say, ''Here l am.
This is what l stand for!''

1091
01:17:31,688 --> 01:17:33,713
lmpeccable standards and...

1092
01:17:33,924 --> 01:17:35,585
...and old-fashioned integrity!

1093
01:17:35,792 --> 01:17:38,625
And if you don't like it,
you can go down the road!

1094
01:17:39,062 --> 01:17:41,121
Gentlemen, you go down that road...

1095
01:17:41,331 --> 01:17:42,764
...you can never come back.

1096
01:17:42,966 --> 01:17:46,458
When you've gone down that road
it's over, it's curtains.

1097
01:17:46,670 --> 01:17:49,070
And l'm not just talking about Panama!

1098
01:17:49,272 --> 01:17:52,332
l'm talking about
the whole human race.

1099
01:18:02,252 --> 01:18:04,686
You too. Get out.

1100
01:18:09,593 --> 01:18:12,061
Harry, l was only kidding, l swear.

1101
01:18:12,529 --> 01:18:16,260
lt's just a sleeve.
l swear to God.

1102
01:18:24,007 --> 01:18:25,565
Teddy came to see Mickie.

1103
01:18:25,775 --> 01:18:29,643
He brought two goons with him.
Said they were Ministry of lnterior.

1104
01:18:29,846 --> 01:18:30,938
Teddy?

1105
01:18:31,214 --> 01:18:33,011
Of course, he's the worst.

1106
01:18:33,216 --> 01:18:35,343
They pay him, the ruling families.

1107
01:18:35,552 --> 01:18:37,782
He takes money to inform
on his friends.

1108
01:18:38,121 --> 01:18:40,180
They were asking around about us.

1109
01:18:40,790 --> 01:18:42,348
They came to me too.

1110
01:18:43,226 --> 01:18:46,627
Thinks we're involved in a
political thing against the system.

1111
01:18:46,830 --> 01:18:48,422
You know, like the old times.

1112
01:18:48,632 --> 01:18:51,100
-You and Marta?
-You and Mickie.

1113
01:18:51,301 --> 01:18:53,098
Why would they think that?

1114
01:18:53,536 --> 01:18:54,798
Maybe you know, Harry.

1115
01:18:57,340 --> 01:18:59,069
l couldn't do it again.

1116
01:19:00,076 --> 01:19:03,637
No more prison.
They break you in there.

1117
01:19:04,814 --> 01:19:08,250
You got so much courage in life.
When it's gone, it's spent.

1118
01:19:09,419 --> 01:19:10,943
l got none left.

1119
01:19:11,154 --> 01:19:14,123
l know what you mean.
l've been there, l know.

1120
01:19:17,661 --> 01:19:18,958
And they came to you?

1121
01:19:20,830 --> 01:19:24,425
Big Chinese guy.
The man who beat her before.

1122
01:19:25,268 --> 01:19:29,102
-What did they do to you?
-Nothing. They wanted information.

1123
01:19:29,306 --> 01:19:33,970
lf l didn't give it to them, they'd
make me look the same, both sides.

1124
01:19:34,177 --> 01:19:36,873
-What information?
-About the two of you.

1125
01:19:37,080 --> 01:19:39,173
How often you meet,
what you talk about.

1126
01:19:39,416 --> 01:19:43,113
l want you both to get out of town.
Take a holiday.

1127
01:19:43,820 --> 01:19:46,311
There's a fireworks festival
in Guarare.

1128
01:19:46,523 --> 01:19:49,219
You love fireworks.
The address is on the label.

1129
01:19:49,426 --> 01:19:51,417
Pete Abuleira lent it to me.

1130
01:19:51,628 --> 01:19:53,357
What are you going to do?

1131
01:19:53,563 --> 01:19:54,996
Sort it out.

1132
01:19:55,732 --> 01:19:57,529
Talk to people l know.

1133
01:20:00,603 --> 01:20:02,468
Better we go in separate cars.

1134
01:20:02,672 --> 01:20:03,866
l follow you later.

1135
01:20:04,074 --> 01:20:05,871
No more drinking now.

1136
01:20:07,577 --> 01:20:09,010
Thanks, Harry.

1137
01:20:09,612 --> 01:20:10,442
Take care.

1138
01:20:15,819 --> 01:20:18,583
l never lied to you, Marta.
You know that.

1139
01:20:18,788 --> 01:20:22,349
l didn't tell you everything,
but what l told you was true.

1140
01:20:22,959 --> 01:20:27,089
There's only so many people you
can do that to. Tell the truth.

1141
01:20:27,630 --> 01:20:30,190
Other people are different.
They need to be....

1142
01:20:30,433 --> 01:20:31,764
Tailored.

1143
01:20:32,202 --> 01:20:33,829
Helped. Yes.

1144
01:20:35,138 --> 01:20:38,107
You flatter them. You make things up.

1145
01:20:39,209 --> 01:20:41,336
They start believing you, Harry.

1146
01:20:41,611 --> 01:20:44,978
Their leading man is one
Michelangelo Abraxas.

1147
01:20:45,348 --> 01:20:48,647
Known to many, l am sure,
as the elusive Pimpernel...

1148
01:20:48,852 --> 01:20:52,913
...of the popularmovement
against General Manuel Noriega.

1149
01:20:53,189 --> 01:20:55,657
Abraxas is a man
ofproven integrity...

1150
01:20:55,859 --> 01:20:58,054
...skilled in clandestine warfare.

1151
01:20:58,728 --> 01:21:00,286
His second in command...

1152
01:21:00,497 --> 01:21:03,432
...but l submit his equal
in skill and resolution...

1153
01:21:03,633 --> 01:21:05,260
...is code name ''Marta.''

1154
01:21:05,668 --> 01:21:09,195
Another veteran of the
anti-Noriega resistance.

1155
01:21:09,706 --> 01:21:13,073
For cover purposes, she is
employed as accountant receptionist...

1156
01:21:13,276 --> 01:21:15,767
...by our own Panamanian head agent...

1157
01:21:15,979 --> 01:21:17,913
...the redoubtable Buchan.

1158
01:21:18,615 --> 01:21:21,675
lf l may say so, Elliot,
a ''Silent Opposition''...

1159
01:21:21,885 --> 01:21:23,910
...doesn't send radio messages.

1160
01:21:24,120 --> 01:21:25,849
Half don't possess telephones.

1161
01:21:26,055 --> 01:21:29,149
Why else would they call
themselves silent?

1162
01:21:29,359 --> 01:21:31,554
They're a life-force, not an embassy.

1163
01:21:32,762 --> 01:21:34,093
Fishermen...

1164
01:21:35,398 --> 01:21:38,629
...small farmers, peasants,
have-nots, penniless students.

1165
01:21:38,835 --> 01:21:41,395
People we wouldn't
entertain in the woodshed.

1166
01:21:41,671 --> 01:21:44,333
So why should we support them, Henry?

1167
01:21:44,541 --> 01:21:46,907
Because if we don't,
someone else will.

1168
01:21:47,110 --> 01:21:50,807
Because the Silent Opposition is
the new Panama in the new millennium.

1169
01:21:51,147 --> 01:21:53,342
And getting in with these chaps...

1170
01:21:53,550 --> 01:21:57,145
...is the sweetest, cheapest
way of saving the canal.

1171
01:21:57,754 --> 01:22:00,655
Do you think personally,
this Abraxas is...

1172
01:22:00,857 --> 01:22:03,451
...presidential material?

1173
01:22:03,660 --> 01:22:04,490
Scotty.

1174
01:22:04,727 --> 01:22:07,696
Abraxas is world-class.
Courageous...

1175
01:22:07,897 --> 01:22:10,764
...unsullied, incorruptible.

1176
01:22:10,967 --> 01:22:13,834
A man to dream of
when you're shaping nations.

1177
01:22:25,548 --> 01:22:29,245
But Abraxas can't go it alone.
He needs our support now.

1178
01:22:29,452 --> 01:22:31,443
lf U.S. military assistance
is guaranteed...

1179
01:22:31,654 --> 01:22:35,055
...Abraxas and his forces will
launch an attack on the government.

1180
01:22:35,325 --> 01:22:39,489
They'll commandeer the radio stations
and the Canal Administration Office.

1181
01:22:39,696 --> 01:22:42,290
Subject, of course,
to advance payment...

1182
01:22:42,499 --> 01:22:44,831
...for arms, equipment
and medical supplies.

1183
01:22:46,069 --> 01:22:47,195
How much?

1184
01:22:48,304 --> 01:22:51,501
The sort of money you boys
leave under the plate, Elliot.

1185
01:22:52,609 --> 01:22:56,010
-How much?
-Twenty million dollars.

1186
01:22:59,482 --> 01:23:02,280
Elliot, may l say a couple
of words, please?

1187
01:23:04,187 --> 01:23:06,417
l'm only a rookie at heart.

1188
01:23:06,623 --> 01:23:11,253
l don't know too much about the ins
and outs of politics, but l know this:

1189
01:23:11,494 --> 01:23:15,931
l was the last American
commander in Panama.

1190
01:23:16,466 --> 01:23:19,902
l had the task of taking
our men out of there.

1191
01:23:21,471 --> 01:23:23,632
Only retreat of my career.

1192
01:23:27,443 --> 01:23:29,104
Broke my heart.

1193
01:23:32,282 --> 01:23:36,241
There is a missing star
on our flag, gentlemen.

1194
01:23:37,887 --> 01:23:42,085
Looks to me that God has
given us a second chance here.

1195
01:23:46,195 --> 01:23:47,423
Yes?

1196
01:23:49,899 --> 01:23:51,059
Sir.

1197
01:23:55,638 --> 01:23:57,105
Encrypted.

1198
01:23:57,974 --> 01:24:00,238
lt went over like ninepins.

1199
01:24:00,443 --> 01:24:02,411
Asked for 20 and guess what?

1200
01:24:02,612 --> 01:24:04,910
They beat me down to 1 5.

1201
01:24:05,114 --> 01:24:06,547
l'm on my way.

1202
01:24:06,749 --> 01:24:08,182
Press play, Andy.

1203
01:24:09,686 --> 01:24:11,620
Teddy! Teddy!

1204
01:24:11,854 --> 01:24:13,947
Why are you hassling Mickie and Marta?

1205
01:24:14,157 --> 01:24:16,250
What are they up to this time, Harry?

1206
01:24:16,459 --> 01:24:19,860
What are you up to?
Spin me one of your stories.

1207
01:24:20,063 --> 01:24:21,860
You stay away from them or else.

1208
01:24:22,065 --> 01:24:25,000
How could you fuck
that faceless half-breed?

1209
01:24:29,038 --> 01:24:30,335
No, no. Relax.

1210
01:24:30,540 --> 01:24:32,770
You're a disgrace to that suit, Teddy.

1211
01:24:34,277 --> 01:24:36,108
-Hey.
-Louisa.

1212
01:24:38,548 --> 01:24:40,914
-There's something l must tell you.
-Okay.

1213
01:24:41,184 --> 01:24:42,310
Lou.

1214
01:24:42,518 --> 01:24:45,351
-l need to talk to you.
-Okay.

1215
01:24:47,090 --> 01:24:48,284
Hello?

1216
01:24:49,525 --> 01:24:50,958
Marta?

1217
01:24:51,194 --> 01:24:54,823
Yeah, it's Louisa. l can't hear you.

1218
01:24:58,568 --> 01:25:00,468
l'll get-- Okay.

1219
01:25:01,404 --> 01:25:02,496
lt's for you.

1220
01:25:11,014 --> 01:25:12,276
lt's me.

1221
01:25:13,082 --> 01:25:16,609
Oh, Harry. l need you. Please come.

1222
01:25:20,423 --> 01:25:22,152
lt's Mickie. He--

1223
01:25:24,160 --> 01:25:25,354
Marta?

1224
01:25:31,868 --> 01:25:34,166
-l've gotta go.
-So it's Marta?

1225
01:25:34,370 --> 01:25:37,396
-All this time, under my nose.
-No, you don't understand.

1226
01:25:37,607 --> 01:25:39,973
Oh, come on, Harry. Please.

1227
01:25:40,510 --> 01:25:41,636
Be a man.

1228
01:25:41,978 --> 01:25:44,845
-Well, if you love her, go.
-Yes, l do love her.

1229
01:25:46,849 --> 01:25:48,908
But l've never made love to her.

1230
01:25:49,118 --> 01:25:50,710
Get out.

1231
01:25:51,654 --> 01:25:53,315
Get out!

1232
01:25:56,325 --> 01:25:57,587
Harry.

1233
01:25:59,996 --> 01:26:01,054
Harry!

1234
01:26:14,544 --> 01:26:16,375
Oh, shit!

1235
01:26:49,946 --> 01:26:52,676
Washington has agreed
that as we have the contacts...

1236
01:26:52,882 --> 01:26:56,147
...that we should undertake
the financing and arming...

1237
01:26:56,352 --> 01:26:58,252
...of the Silent Opposition.

1238
01:26:58,454 --> 01:27:02,083
And it's been agreed that that task
be undertaken by an older hand.

1239
01:27:02,291 --> 01:27:06,819
By myself, in fact. And on
a more formal basis than hitherto.

1240
01:27:07,463 --> 01:27:10,728
l dare say that'll come
as a bit of a relief to you, Andrew.

1241
01:27:10,933 --> 01:27:13,128
Equipping an army, tedious business.

1242
01:27:13,336 --> 01:27:16,328
Not the sort of task
for your mercurial brain.

1243
01:27:16,539 --> 01:27:19,167
Best left to us humble
planners and plodders, eh?

1244
01:27:19,876 --> 01:27:24,245
lt's fine in principle, Scotty.
Just one snag.

1245
01:27:24,547 --> 01:27:26,378
They won't talk to anyone but me.

1246
01:27:28,184 --> 01:27:30,709
l think you'll find that,
however shy they are...

1247
01:27:30,920 --> 01:27:33,047
...they'll talk to a candid friend...

1248
01:27:33,256 --> 01:27:35,747
...who has $1 5 million
to spend on them.

1249
01:27:36,492 --> 01:27:38,119
Wouldn't you say, ambassador?

1250
01:27:38,928 --> 01:27:42,022
You know, for quite a while
l was skeptical...

1251
01:27:42,231 --> 01:27:45,496
...about this extraordinarily
silent opposition.

1252
01:27:45,701 --> 01:27:50,729
And l always thought that Mickie
Abraxas was just a harmless drunk.

1253
01:27:51,207 --> 01:27:53,368
Funny how wrong you can be.

1254
01:27:54,877 --> 01:27:59,610
Andy may have a real problem conjuring
up one of these people for you.

1255
01:28:00,049 --> 01:28:03,382
Afraid so, Scotty.
You could put it like this:

1256
01:28:03,586 --> 01:28:07,522
lf you don't go through me,
there is no Silent Opposition.

1257
01:28:07,723 --> 01:28:09,918
lt doesn't do to be too possessive.

1258
01:28:10,126 --> 01:28:13,755
We must be brave and wean them off
the Osnard teat, my boy.

1259
01:28:14,397 --> 01:28:18,800
Might l offer myself
as a go-between, so to speak...

1260
01:28:19,001 --> 01:28:22,630
...to verify Andy's dispersal
of these funds?

1261
01:28:23,239 --> 01:28:25,935
Kind of you to offer, ambassador.
Perhaps so.

1262
01:28:26,142 --> 01:28:29,043
Meanwhile, Andrew can brief me
on the details.

1263
01:28:29,245 --> 01:28:31,179
We have a lot to catch up on, eh?

1264
01:28:31,380 --> 01:28:34,543
Whiskey till the small hours
in the privacy of your abode...

1265
01:28:34,750 --> 01:28:37,685
...is indicated for Osnard
and Luxmore, l believe.

1266
01:28:39,655 --> 01:28:41,714
-Sure.
-Excellent, gentlemen.

1267
01:28:41,924 --> 01:28:45,155
Andrew, l take it you have
a secure safe in your apartment?

1268
01:28:45,361 --> 01:28:46,851
Absolutely, sir.

1269
01:28:47,129 --> 01:28:48,221
Fort Knox.

1270
01:28:48,431 --> 01:28:49,728
Ambassador.

1271
01:28:50,166 --> 01:28:51,531
l'll get my files.

1272
01:29:01,711 --> 01:29:04,874
-You are getting out, aren't you?
-Possibly.

1273
01:29:06,048 --> 01:29:07,777
Too early to say.

1274
01:29:08,217 --> 01:29:09,684
You'll have to, won't you?

1275
01:29:09,886 --> 01:29:12,821
l mean, there is no
Silent Opposition, is there?

1276
01:29:13,890 --> 01:29:16,882
-Who told you that?
-You did, just now in the meeting.

1277
01:29:18,160 --> 01:29:20,185
You made it all up, didn't you?

1278
01:29:22,465 --> 01:29:24,296
What are you talking about?

1279
01:29:24,500 --> 01:29:27,731
l think you're the wickedest
human being l've ever met.

1280
01:29:31,040 --> 01:29:33,201
That was the attraction, wasn't it?

1281
01:29:34,410 --> 01:29:36,139
How about a farewell fuck?

1282
01:29:36,579 --> 01:29:38,171
Here in the office.

1283
01:29:38,848 --> 01:29:40,338
A knee-trembler.

1284
01:29:43,753 --> 01:29:46,187
You know, l think l'm cured.

1285
01:29:47,623 --> 01:29:51,423
Excuse me, Francesca.
A private word with Andrew.

1286
01:29:51,894 --> 01:29:53,418
He's all yours.

1287
01:29:56,299 --> 01:30:00,429
My duty is to inform
the Foreign Office of this...

1288
01:30:00,703 --> 01:30:02,102
...travesty.

1289
01:30:03,572 --> 01:30:05,164
How much is your duty worth?

1290
01:30:06,642 --> 01:30:07,870
-Two million.
-One.

1291
01:30:08,077 --> 01:30:09,601
-One and a half.
-One and a quarter.

1292
01:30:09,812 --> 01:30:11,006
Done.

1293
01:30:11,781 --> 01:30:13,078
Andrew.

1294
01:30:13,549 --> 01:30:14,880
Good night.

1295
01:30:42,945 --> 01:30:47,348
You got a lovely little family, Harry.
Only one thing can spoil it.

1296
01:30:47,984 --> 01:30:50,418
-What's that, Uncle Benny?
-The truth, Harry.

1297
01:30:50,619 --> 01:30:52,052
That's the honest truth.

1298
01:31:00,296 --> 01:31:01,820
Esmeralda?

1299
01:31:02,631 --> 01:31:03,620
Esmeralda.

1300
01:31:06,335 --> 01:31:08,895
l'm going out. Watch the children.

1301
01:31:10,039 --> 01:31:11,700
Marta!

1302
01:31:17,346 --> 01:31:19,041
Marta!

1303
01:31:33,162 --> 01:31:35,357
Oh, God!

1304
01:31:35,998 --> 01:31:37,966
l'm not imposing on you, am l?

1305
01:31:38,167 --> 01:31:40,601
You're not imposing
on me in the least.

1306
01:31:43,773 --> 01:31:45,001
Who the devil's that?

1307
01:31:53,516 --> 01:31:55,006
Buchan 2. We got trouble.

1308
01:31:55,217 --> 01:31:57,947
When l get her into
the other room, get out.

1309
01:31:58,154 --> 01:32:00,452
ln the lobby,
give the concierge a dollar.

1310
01:32:00,656 --> 01:32:03,784
He'll get you a taxi to
the El Panama Hotel. Get a room.

1311
01:32:03,993 --> 01:32:05,722
A taxi? At this time of night?

1312
01:32:05,928 --> 01:32:08,761
l don't speak Spanish, Andy.
l'm unarmed.

1313
01:32:08,964 --> 01:32:10,522
Life is cheap here.

1314
01:32:10,733 --> 01:32:13,930
You can handle it.
You're a field man, aren't you?

1315
01:32:14,737 --> 01:32:16,136
What about the bags?

1316
01:32:16,338 --> 01:32:19,000
l'll guard them with my life.
Believe me.

1317
01:32:44,834 --> 01:32:46,131
Louisa.

1318
01:32:47,303 --> 01:32:50,761
-Something on your mind?
-What the fuck have you done?

1319
01:32:51,073 --> 01:32:54,770
What is all this bullshit
about Abraxas and Delgado?

1320
01:32:54,977 --> 01:32:57,946
Don't worry. lt's nothing.
lt's crap. lt's all a game.

1321
01:32:58,147 --> 01:32:59,774
-Where's Harry?
-Harry's okay.

1322
01:32:59,982 --> 01:33:03,782
-l'm gonna take care of Harry and you.
-Get your fucking hands off me!

1323
01:33:03,986 --> 01:33:05,783
Get off me.

1324
01:33:09,358 --> 01:33:10,825
Relax.

1325
01:33:11,527 --> 01:33:13,722
We both know why you're here.

1326
01:33:19,034 --> 01:33:20,296
Yeah.

1327
01:33:20,603 --> 01:33:23,163
Shit! You....

1328
01:33:27,376 --> 01:33:29,708
What have you gotten Harry into?

1329
01:33:29,912 --> 01:33:33,712
Harry got himself into this
with his own ludicrous stories.

1330
01:33:34,150 --> 01:33:38,450
When the Americans take back their
canal, it'll be down to him, not me.

1331
01:33:39,622 --> 01:33:40,646
When?

1332
01:33:41,757 --> 01:33:42,746
When?

1333
01:33:45,060 --> 01:33:46,857
Get out of my way!

1334
01:33:50,533 --> 01:33:52,262
l killed him, Marta.

1335
01:33:52,468 --> 01:33:54,936
l killed him with my bullshit.

1336
01:33:55,804 --> 01:33:58,102
He said the police were after him.

1337
01:33:58,307 --> 01:33:59,569
He said:

1338
01:34:01,177 --> 01:34:03,168
''Tell Harry l'm sorry.''

1339
01:34:03,445 --> 01:34:06,039
And l didn't finish his suit.

1340
01:34:06,882 --> 01:34:09,578
lt would've given him
back his dignity.

1341
01:34:10,219 --> 01:34:12,312
He wouldn't have shot himself in it.

1342
01:34:12,521 --> 01:34:15,012
He was always going to do it.

1343
01:34:16,959 --> 01:34:20,156
He was just looking
for a good enough excuse.

1344
01:34:41,383 --> 01:34:43,283
Shall l close his eyes?

1345
01:34:56,065 --> 01:34:58,033
You must go now, Harry.

1346
01:34:59,401 --> 01:35:00,493
Go, Harry.

1347
01:35:22,958 --> 01:35:23,947
Yep.

1348
01:35:24,293 --> 01:35:26,284
Harry, my man, where have you been?

1349
01:35:26,495 --> 01:35:30,693
Louisa was here. l think she thought
l was leading you astray or something.

1350
01:35:33,736 --> 01:35:34,998
Jesus.

1351
01:35:36,071 --> 01:35:38,039
l see. Go on.

1352
01:35:38,540 --> 01:35:40,838
So we have to stop all this, you hear?

1353
01:35:41,377 --> 01:35:44,972
Mickie knew nothing about it.
You know and l know l made it all up.

1354
01:35:45,180 --> 01:35:48,274
lt's too late for that, old boy.
Out of ourhands.

1355
01:35:48,884 --> 01:35:51,546
A case of life imitating art.

1356
01:36:06,769 --> 01:36:08,532
Bit of a setback, sir.

1357
01:36:08,737 --> 01:36:10,762
lt's Mickie Abraxas.

1358
01:36:11,273 --> 01:36:12,831
Bullet through the head.

1359
01:36:13,842 --> 01:36:14,900
Suicide.

1360
01:36:15,110 --> 01:36:18,307
Setback? Setback? On the contrary.

1361
01:36:18,514 --> 01:36:22,006
No, they'll probably claim
he killed himself in police custody.

1362
01:36:22,217 --> 01:36:26,278
That's standard euphemism for
assassinations in regimes of this ilk.

1363
01:36:26,488 --> 01:36:28,820
No, no one's going
to swallow that one.

1364
01:36:29,024 --> 01:36:30,013
No.

1365
01:36:30,659 --> 01:36:34,686
''Leader of the Democratic Rebel
Movement murdered.''

1366
01:36:34,897 --> 01:36:38,833
Yes. l think we could have
the peg we're looking for, Andy.

1367
01:36:39,034 --> 01:36:41,935
l'll inform ourAmerican cousins.
Now, tell me...

1368
01:36:42,137 --> 01:36:45,334
...did you manage to resolve
that Buchan 2 situation?

1369
01:36:45,541 --> 01:36:49,773
l got the distinct impression
she was in a state ofhigh anxiety.

1370
01:36:49,978 --> 01:36:54,813
You must impress on your operatives
the importance ofstaying in control.

1371
01:36:55,017 --> 01:36:56,109
Andrew?

1372
01:37:11,200 --> 01:37:14,226
Hello, is anybody there?
l must talk to the ambassador.

1373
01:37:14,436 --> 01:37:15,494
l'm English.

1374
01:37:15,704 --> 01:37:19,003
lt's a matter of grave importance.

1375
01:37:25,781 --> 01:37:29,217
Mickie Abraxas died three hours ago.

1376
01:37:29,418 --> 01:37:32,546
Executed by a government death squad.

1377
01:37:33,155 --> 01:37:35,419
l have informed the president.

1378
01:37:35,624 --> 01:37:38,184
He has authorized us to go on in.

1379
01:37:38,394 --> 01:37:41,921
We have that right under the treaty
if the canal is threatened.

1380
01:37:42,731 --> 01:37:45,723
Operation Straight Arrow
is all yours, general.

1381
01:37:45,934 --> 01:37:47,697
How soon can you be operational?

1382
01:37:47,903 --> 01:37:50,997
-Give me four hours, sir.
-That fast?

1383
01:37:51,440 --> 01:37:55,206
My rapid response units
are on full alert, sir.

1384
01:37:55,411 --> 01:37:58,505
Carrier Alaska is
off the coast of Panama.

1385
01:37:58,714 --> 01:38:01,581
Eight F-22 Raptors are on alert.

1386
01:38:01,784 --> 01:38:05,345
Twelve gunships.
A battalion of marines.

1387
01:38:06,822 --> 01:38:10,121
-l've got to speak to the ambassador.
-The ambassador is busy.

1388
01:38:10,325 --> 01:38:12,225
You'll have to come back tomorrow.

1389
01:38:12,428 --> 01:38:13,918
Ambassador.

1390
01:38:14,430 --> 01:38:16,330
l am Buchan.

1391
01:38:16,632 --> 01:38:21,194
l made it all up. You've got
to stop it. You see, l'm Buchan.

1392
01:38:21,403 --> 01:38:24,372
l'm sorry, but aren't you
that tailor fellow?

1393
01:38:24,573 --> 01:38:25,904
You're rather upset.

1394
01:38:26,108 --> 01:38:28,975
-Nigel, please show the gentleman out.
-Yes.

1395
01:38:29,178 --> 01:38:31,874
There is no Silent Opposition!

1396
01:38:32,080 --> 01:38:35,015
Someone's gotta blow the whistle.
Might as well be me.

1397
01:38:35,217 --> 01:38:39,244
You're a diplomat. Be diplomatic.
Can't interfere at this stage.

1398
01:38:39,455 --> 01:38:42,322
lt would reflect very badly.
And what could we say?

1399
01:38:42,524 --> 01:38:47,461
That some deranged tailor Johnny
told us it was all a joke?

1400
01:38:47,663 --> 01:38:48,687
Nevertheless.

1401
01:38:54,636 --> 01:38:57,298
-Darling, what--?
-l need to talk to Ernesto.

1402
01:39:04,847 --> 01:39:05,677
Andy.

1403
01:39:14,923 --> 01:39:15,855
Andy!

1404
01:39:20,996 --> 01:39:22,088
Wait!

1405
01:39:34,743 --> 01:39:36,142
Oh, Harry.

1406
01:39:49,658 --> 01:39:52,456
Well, if the ambassador's
been recalled...

1407
01:39:52,661 --> 01:39:55,061
...give me somebody
who hasn't been recalled.

1408
01:39:55,264 --> 01:39:58,392
His secretary, his butler, his--

1409
01:40:00,469 --> 01:40:02,096
Come with me, Louisa.

1410
01:40:03,171 --> 01:40:05,196
We're going to see the president.

1411
01:40:17,819 --> 01:40:19,286
Shit!

1412
01:40:23,926 --> 01:40:25,826
Oh, no, no, no.

1413
01:40:26,028 --> 01:40:28,462
Come on, come on, come on.

1414
01:41:10,739 --> 01:41:12,673
What the fuck do you want?

1415
01:41:12,874 --> 01:41:17,607
l want you to come back to the embassy
and tell them it's all a mistake!

1416
01:41:18,347 --> 01:41:21,839
Harry, l've got our money here.
Yours and mine.

1417
01:41:22,050 --> 01:41:24,883
l'm trying to get out
before they close the airport.

1418
01:41:25,087 --> 01:41:29,251
l'm going straight to Switzerland.
Open numbered accounts for both of us.

1419
01:41:29,558 --> 01:41:32,152
You'll be a rich man.
Just give me a lift.

1420
01:41:32,361 --> 01:41:34,386
-We're going back.
-Get out of my way!

1421
01:41:34,596 --> 01:41:38,293
-Are you not listening to me?
-Don't be bloody annoying, Harry!

1422
01:41:40,202 --> 01:41:43,035
Shit! They're here.

1423
01:42:06,028 --> 01:42:07,086
Ambassador!

1424
01:42:09,064 --> 01:42:13,160
Will you vouch for me, my credentials?
l need to get on a plane.

1425
01:42:13,368 --> 01:42:15,962
You wish for this man to be included?

1426
01:42:16,171 --> 01:42:18,139
l've never seen him before.

1427
01:42:20,375 --> 01:42:21,740
Ambassador.

1428
01:42:25,881 --> 01:42:29,942
As you can see, the airport is closed,
but palms have been greased.

1429
01:42:30,152 --> 01:42:35,089
And once our arrangement
has been concluded...

1430
01:42:35,657 --> 01:42:37,648
...you'll be free to go.

1431
01:42:53,175 --> 01:42:57,635
lt is a fabrication, Mr. President.
A pack of lies, a travesty.

1432
01:42:57,846 --> 01:43:02,078
The canal is safe, secure.
Unthreatened.

1433
01:43:02,284 --> 01:43:04,309
Call off your dogs, sir.

1434
01:43:04,519 --> 01:43:06,180
Call them off.

1435
01:43:11,827 --> 01:43:13,886
l'll walk you to your plane.

1436
01:43:17,432 --> 01:43:20,401
Could this be the beginning
of a beautiful friendship?

1437
01:43:20,602 --> 01:43:23,264
l think it desperately unlikely.

1438
01:43:27,843 --> 01:43:31,074
Mission aborted. Return to base.

1439
01:43:44,159 --> 01:43:45,285
Why?

1440
01:43:45,961 --> 01:43:47,519
l don't know.

1441
01:43:49,264 --> 01:43:50,891
l thought it was a game.

1442
01:43:51,099 --> 01:43:53,033
And behind my back?

1443
01:43:53,235 --> 01:43:56,102
All those lies about
the president and Delgado?

1444
01:43:56,571 --> 01:43:59,005
Oh, yes, the lies.

1445
01:43:59,975 --> 01:44:02,842
l'm very, very sorry about the lies.

1446
01:44:06,915 --> 01:44:08,177
Louisa....

1447
01:44:08,950 --> 01:44:11,646
l never did work in Savile Row, did l?

1448
01:44:11,853 --> 01:44:13,320
Not as such.

1449
01:44:14,189 --> 01:44:16,487
l learned the tailoring in prison.

1450
01:44:17,159 --> 01:44:20,560
l burnt down my Uncle Benny's
warehouse to help him out.

1451
01:44:20,762 --> 01:44:22,787
And then, when l'd done my time...

1452
01:44:23,365 --> 01:44:26,232
...Uncle Benny,
he gives me my portion...

1453
01:44:27,202 --> 01:44:29,966
...sends me out here
so l can't get into trouble.

1454
01:44:31,239 --> 01:44:33,707
l pretended he was Arthur Braithwaite.

1455
01:44:39,181 --> 01:44:41,809
You see, lying's what
you do in prison, Lou.

1456
01:44:42,751 --> 01:44:44,878
lt's instead of love, really.

1457
01:44:45,287 --> 01:44:49,018
You tell it the way it should be
since that's better than how it is...

1458
01:44:49,224 --> 01:44:50,657
...when it's that bad.

1459
01:44:50,892 --> 01:44:52,382
lf you follow me.

1460
01:44:53,295 --> 01:44:55,991
Why didn't you just tell me
from the start?

1461
01:44:58,733 --> 01:45:01,998
Because l fell in love
with you, my princess.

1462
01:45:04,706 --> 01:45:07,539
And l knew that l wasn't
good enough for you.

1463
01:45:09,077 --> 01:45:10,635
Not as l stood.

1464
01:45:13,281 --> 01:45:16,011
Harry, you are such a fool.

1465
01:45:18,186 --> 01:45:22,680
Dad, you promised to tell me a story.
Where were you?

1466
01:45:23,558 --> 01:45:25,048
Oh, Sarah.

1467
01:45:25,927 --> 01:45:27,485
l'm so sorry.

1468
01:45:30,265 --> 01:45:33,029
No need to cry about it, Dad.

1469
01:45:34,269 --> 01:45:35,463
Hi, Dad.

1470
01:45:35,670 --> 01:45:36,898
Hi, Mum.

1471
01:45:40,542 --> 01:45:42,601
So, what do you want me to do?

1472
01:45:44,946 --> 01:45:46,811
What do l want you to do?

1473
01:45:48,283 --> 01:45:49,875
What you always do.

1474
01:45:54,556 --> 01:45:56,080
Make breakfast.

1475
01:45:59,427 --> 01:46:01,520
Can we have pancakes?

1476
01:46:03,431 --> 01:46:05,456
-Yeah.
-You want pancakes?

1477
01:46:06,134 --> 01:46:07,465
Breakfast?

1478
01:46:19,748 --> 01:46:23,684
Well, there's two ways we can deal
with this one, my dear.

1479
01:46:23,885 --> 01:46:24,943
Ready?

1480
01:46:30,058 --> 01:46:31,787
Hooray!

